db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23576, line : "40 The following argument of the Iliad, corrected in a few particulars,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23577, line : "is translated from Bitaube, and is, perhaps, the neatest summary"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23578, line : "that has ever been drawn up:--\"A hero, injured by his general, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23579, line : "animated with a noble resentment, retires to his tent; and for a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23580, line : "season withdraws himself and his troops from the war. During this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23581, line : "interval, victory abandons the army, which for nine years has been"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23582, line : "occupied in a great enterprise, upon the successful termination of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23583, line : "which the honour of their country depends. The general, at length"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23584, line : "opening his eyes to the fault which he had committed, deputes the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23585, line : "principal officers of his army to the incensed hero, with commission"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23586, line : "to make compensation for the injury, and to tender magnificent"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23587, line : "presents. The hero, according to the proud obstinacy of his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23588, line : "character, persists in his animosity; the army is again defeated,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23589, line : "and is on the verge of entire destruction. This inexorable man has a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23590, line : "friend; this friend weeps before him, and asks for the hero's arms,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23591, line : "and for permission to go to the war in his stead. The eloquence of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23592, line : "friendship prevails more than the intercession of the ambassadors or"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23593, line : "the gifts of the general. He lends his armour to his friend, but"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23594, line : "commands him not to engage with the chief of the enemy's army,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23595, line : "because he reserves to himself the honour of that combat, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23596, line : "because he also fears for his friend's life. The prohibition is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23597, line : "forgotten; the friend listens to nothing but his courage; his corpse"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23598, line : "is brought back to the hero, and the hero's arms become the prize of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23599, line : "the conqueror. Then the hero, given up to the most lively despair,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23600, line : "prepares to fight; he receives from a divinity new armour, is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23601, line : "reconciled with his general and, thirsting for glory and revenge,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23602, line : "enacts prodigies of valour, recovers the victory, slays the enemy's"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23603, line : "chief, honours his friend with superb funeral rites, and exercises a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23604, line : "cruel vengeance on the body of his destroyer; but finally appeased"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23605, line : "by the tears and prayers of the father of the slain warrior,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23606, line : "restores to the old man the corpse of his son, which he buries with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23607, line : "due solemnities.'--Coleridge, p. 177, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23609, line : "41 Vultures: Pope is more accurate than the poet he translates, for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23610, line : "Homer writes \"a prey to dogs and to _all_ kinds of birds. But all"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23611, line : "kinds of birds are not carnivorous."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23613, line : "42 --_i.e._ during the whole time of their striving the will of Jove was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23614, line : "being gradually accomplished."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23616, line : "43 Compare Milton's \"Paradise Lost\" i. 6"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23618, line : "\"Sing, heavenly Muse, that on the secret top"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23619, line : "Of Horeb, or of Sinai, didst inspire"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23620, line : "That shepherd.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23622, line : "44 --_Latona's son: i.e._ Apollo."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23624, line : "45 --_King of men:_ Agamemnon."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23626, line : "46 --_Brother kings:_ Menelaus and Agamemnon."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23628, line : "47 --_Smintheus_ an epithet taken from sminthos, the Phrygian name for a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23629, line : "_mouse,_ was applied to Apollo for having put an end to a plague of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23630, line : "mice which had harassed that territory. Strabo, however, says, that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23631, line : "when the Teucri were migrating from Crete, they were told by an"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23632, line : "oracle to settle in that place, where they should not be attacked by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23633, line : "the original inhabitants of the land, and that, having halted for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23634, line : "the night, a number of field-mice came and gnawed away the leathern"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23635, line : "straps of their baggage, and thongs of their armour. In fulfilment"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23636, line : "of the oracle, they settled on the spot, and raised a temple to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23637, line : "Sminthean Apollo. Grote, \"History of Greece,\" i. p. 68, remarks that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23638, line : "the \"worship of Sminthean Apollo, in various parts of the Troad and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23639, line : "its neighboring territory, dates before the earliest period of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23640, line : "Aeolian colonization.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23642, line : "48 --_Cilla,_ a town of Troas near Thebe, so called from Cillus, a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23643, line : "sister of Hippodamia, slain by OEnomaus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23645, line : "49 A mistake. It should be,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23648, line : "\"If e'er I _roofed_ thy graceful fane,\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23651, line : "for the custom of decorating temples with garlands was of later"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23652, line : "date."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23654, line : "50 --_Bent was his bow_ \"The Apollo of Homer, it must be borne in mind,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23655, line : "is a different character from the deity of the same name in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23656, line : "later classical pantheon. Throughout both poems, all deaths from"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23657, line : "unforeseen or invisible causes, the ravages of pestilence, the fate"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23658, line : "of the young child or promising adult, cut off in the germ of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23659, line : "infancy or flower of youth, of the old man dropping peacefully into"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23660, line : "the grave, or of the reckless sinner suddenly checked in his career"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23661, line : "of crime, are ascribed to the arrows of Apollo or Diana. The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23662, line : "oracular functions of the god rose naturally out of the above"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23663, line : "fundamental attributes, for who could more appropriately impart to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23664, line : "mortals what little foreknowledge Fate permitted of her decrees than"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23665, line : "the agent of her most awful dispensations? The close union of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23666, line : "arts of prophecy and song explains his additional office of god of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23667, line : "music, while the arrows with which he and his sister were armed,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23668, line : "symbols of sudden death in every age, no less naturally procured him"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23669, line : "that of god of archery. Of any connection between Apollo and the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23670, line : "Sun, whatever may have existed in the more esoteric doctrine of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23671, line : "Greek sanctuaries, there is no trace in either Iliad or"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23672, line : "Odyssey.\"--Mure, \"History of Greek Literature,\" vol. i. p. 478, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23674, line : "51 It has frequently been observed, that most pestilences begin with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23675, line : "animals, and that Homer had this fact in mind."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23677, line : "52 --_Convened to council._ The public assembly in the heroic times is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23678, line : "well characterized by Grote, vol. ii. p 92. \"It is an assembly for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23679, line : "talk. Communication and discussion to a certain extent by the chiefs"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23680, line : "in person, of the people as listeners and sympathizers--often for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23681, line : "eloquence, and sometimes for quarrel--but here its ostensible"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23682, line : "purposes end.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23684, line : "53 Old Jacob Duport, whose \"Gnomologia Homerica\" is full of curious and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23685, line : "useful things, quotes several passages of the ancients, in which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23686, line : "reference is made to these words of Homer, in maintenance of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23687, line : "belief that dreams had a divine origin and an import in which men"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23688, line : "were interested."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23690, line : "54 Rather, \"bright-eyed.\" See the German critics quoted by Arnold."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23692, line : "55 The prize given to Ajax was Tecmessa, while Ulysses received"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23693, line : "Laodice, the daughter of Cycnus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23695, line : "56 The Myrmidons dwelt on the southern borders of Thessaly, and took"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23696, line : "their origin from Myrmido, son of Jupiter and Eurymedusa. It is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23697, line : "fancifully supposed that the name was derived from myrmaex, an"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23698, line : "_ant,_ \"because they imitated the diligence of the ants, and like"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23699, line : "them were indefatigable, continually employed in cultivating the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23700, line : "earth; the change from ants to men is founded merely on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23701, line : "equivocation of their name, which resembles that of the ant: they"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23702, line : "bore a further resemblance to these little animals, in that instead"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23703, line : "of inhabiting towns or villages, at first they commonly resided in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23704, line : "the open fields, having no other retreats but dens and the cavities"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23705, line : "of trees, until Ithacus brought them together, and settled them in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23706, line : "more secure and comfortable habitations.\"--Anthon's \"Lempriere.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23708, line : "57 Eustathius, after Heraclides Ponticus and others, allegorizes this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23709, line : "apparition, as if the appearance of Minerva to Achilles, unseen by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23710, line : "the rest, was intended to point out the sudden recollection that he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23711, line : "would gain nothing by intemperate wrath, and that it were best to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23712, line : "restrain his anger, and only gratify it by withdrawing his services."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23713, line : "The same idea is rather cleverly worked out by Apuleius, \"De Deo"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23714, line : "Socratis.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23716, line : "58 Compare Milton, \"Paradise Lost,\" bk. ii:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23718, line : "\"Though his tongue"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23719, line : "Dropp'd manna.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23721, line : "So Proverbs v. 3, \"For the lips of a strange woman drop as an"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23722, line : "honey-comb.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23724, line : "59 Salt water was chiefly used in lustrations, from its being supposed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23725, line : "to possess certain fiery particles. Hence, if sea-water could not be"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23726, line : "obtained, salt was thrown into the fresh water to be used for the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23727, line : "lustration. Menander, in Clem. Alex. vii. p.713, hydati perriranai,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23728, line : "embalon alas, phakois."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23730, line : "60 The persons of heralds were held inviolable, and they were at"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23731, line : "liberty to travel whither they would without fear of molestation."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23732, line : "Pollux, Onom. viii. p. 159. The office was generally given to old"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23733, line : "men, and they were believed to be under the especial protection of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23734, line : "Jove and Mercury."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23736, line : "61 His mother, Thetis, the daughter of Nereus and Doris, who was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23737, line : "courted by Neptune and Jupiter. When, however, it was known that the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23738, line : "son to whom she would give birth must prove greater than his father,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23739, line : "it was determined to wed her to a mortal, and Peleus, with great"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23740, line : "difficulty, succeeded in obtaining her hand, as she eluded him by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23741, line : "assuming various forms. Her children were all destroyed by fire"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23742, line : "through her attempts to see whether they were immortal, and Achilles"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23743, line : "would have shared the same fate had not his father rescued him. She"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23744, line : "afterwards rendered him invulnerable by plunging him into the waters"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23745, line : "of the Styx, with the exception of that part of the heel by which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23746, line : "she held him. Hygin. Fab. 54"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23748, line : "62 Thebe was a city of Mysia, north of Adramyttium."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23750, line : "63 That is, defrauds me of the prize allotted me by their votes."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23752, line : "64 Quintus Calaber goes still further in his account of the service"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23753, line : "rendered to Jove by Thetis:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23755, line : "\"Nay more, the fetters of Almighty Jove"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23756, line : "She loosed\"--Dyce's \"Calaber,\" s. 58."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23758, line : "65 --_To Fates averse._ Of the gloomy destiny reigning throughout the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23759, line : "Homeric poems, and from which even the gods are not exempt, Schlegel"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23760, line : "well observes, \"This power extends also to the world of gods-- for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23761, line : "the Grecian gods are mere powers of nature--and although immeasurably"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23762, line : "higher than mortal man, yet, compared with infinitude, they are on"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23763, line : "an equal footing with himself.\"--'Lectures on the Drama' v. p. 67."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23765, line : "66 It has been observed that the annual procession of the sacred ship"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23766, line : "so often represented on Egyptian monuments, and the return of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23767, line : "deity from Ethiopia after some days' absence, serves to show the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23768, line : "Ethiopian origin of Thebes, and of the worship of Jupiter Ammon. \"I"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23769, line : "think,\" says Heeren, after quoting a passage from Diodorus about the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23770, line : "holy ship, \"that this procession is represented in one of the great"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23771, line : "sculptured reliefs on the temple of Karnak. The sacred ship of Ammon"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23772, line : "is on the shore with its whole equipment, and is towed along by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23773, line : "another boat. It is therefore on its voyage. This must have been one"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23774, line : "of the most celebrated festivals, since, even according to the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23775, line : "interpretation of antiquity, Homer alludes to it when he speaks of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23776, line : "Jupiter's visit to the Ethiopians, and his twelve days'"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23777, line : "absence.\"--Long, \"Egyptian Antiquities\" vol. 1 p. 96. Eustathius,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23778, line : "vol. 1 p. 98, sq. (ed. Basil) gives this interpretation, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23779, line : "likewise an allegorical one, which we will spare the reader."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23781, line : "67 --_Atoned,_ i.e. reconciled. This is the proper and most natural"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23782, line : "meaning of the word, as may be seen from Taylor's remarks in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23783, line : "Calmet's Dictionary, p.110, of my edition."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23785, line : "68 That is, drawing back their necks while they cut their throats. \"If"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23786, line : "the sacrifice was in honour of the celestial gods, the throat was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23787, line : "bent upwards towards heaven; but if made to the heroes, or infernal"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23788, line : "deities, it was killed with its throat toward the ground.\"-- \"Elgin"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23789, line : "Marbles,\" vol i. p.81."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23791, line : "\"The jolly crew, unmindful of the past,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23792, line : "The quarry share, their plenteous dinner haste,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23793, line : "Some strip the skin; some portion out the spoil;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23794, line : "The limbs yet trembling, in the caldrons boil;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23795, line : "Some on the fire the reeking entrails broil."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23796, line : "Stretch'd on the grassy turf, at ease they dine,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23797, line : "Restore their strength with meat, and cheer their souls with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23798, line : "wine.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23800, line : "Dryden's \"Virgil,\" i. 293."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23802, line : "69 --_Crown'd, i.e._ filled to the brim. The custom of adorning goblets"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23803, line : "with flowers was of later date."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23805, line : "70 --_He spoke,_ &c. \"When a friend inquired of Phidias what pattern he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23806, line : "had formed his Olympian Jupiter, he is said to have answered by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23807, line : "repeating the lines of the first Iliad in which the poet represents"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23808, line : "the majesty of the god in the most sublime terms; thereby signifying"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23809, line : "that the genius of Homer had inspired him with it. Those who beheld"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23810, line : "this statue are said to have been so struck with it as to have asked"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23811, line : "whether Jupiter had descended from heaven to show himself to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23812, line : "Phidias, or whether Phidias had been carried thither to contemplate"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23813, line : "the god.\"-- \"Elgin Marbles,\" vol. xii p.124."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23815, line : "71 \"So was his will"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23816, line : "Pronounced among the gods, and by an oath,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23817, line : "That shook heav'n's whole circumference, confirm'd.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23819, line : "\"Paradise Lost\" ii. 351."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23821, line : "72 --_A double bowl, i.e._ a vessel with a cup at both ends, something"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23822, line : "like the measures by which a halfpenny or pennyworth of nuts is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23823, line : "sold. See Buttmann, Lexic. p. 93 sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23825, line : "73 \"Paradise Lost,\" i. 44."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23827, line : "\"Him th' Almighty power"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23828, line : "Hurl'd headlong flaming from th ethereal sky,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23829, line : "With hideous ruin and combustion\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23831, line : "74 The occasion on which Vulcan incurred Jove's displeasure was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23832, line : "this--After Hercules, had taken and pillaged Troy, Juno raised a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23833, line : "storm, which drove him to the island of Cos, having previously cast"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23834, line : "Jove into a sleep, to prevent him aiding his son. Jove, in revenge,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23835, line : "fastened iron anvils to her feet, and hung her from the sky, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23836, line : "Vulcan, attempting to relieve her, was kicked down from Olympus in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23837, line : "the manner described. The allegorists have gone mad in finding deep"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23838, line : "explanations for this amusing fiction. See Heraclides, 'Ponticus,\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23839, line : "p. 463 sq., ed Gale. The story is told by Homer himself in Book xv."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23840, line : "The Sinthians were a race of robbers, the ancient inhabitants of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23841, line : "Lemnos which island was ever after sacred to Vulcan."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23843, line : "\"Nor was his name unheard or unadored"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23844, line : "In ancient Greece, and in Ausonian land"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23845, line : "Men call'd him Mulciber, and how he fell"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23846, line : "From heaven, they fabled, thrown by angry Jove"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23847, line : "Sheer o'er the crystal battlements from morn"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23848, line : "To noon he fell, from noon to dewy eve,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23849, line : "A summer's day and with the setting sun"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23850, line : "Dropp'd from the zenith like a falling star"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23851, line : "On Lemnos, th' Aegean isle thus they relate.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23853, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" i. 738"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23855, line : "75 It is ingeniously observed by Grote, vol i p. 463, that \"The gods"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23856, line : "formed a sort of political community of their own which had its"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23857, line : "hierarchy, its distribution of ranks and duties, its contentions for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23858, line : "power and occasional revolutions, its public meetings in the agora"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23859, line : "of Olympus, and its multitudinous banquets or festivals.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23861, line : "76 Plato, Rep. iii. p. 437, was so scandalized at this deception of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23862, line : "Jupiter's, and at his other attacks on the character of the gods,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23863, line : "that he would fain sentence him to an honourable banishment. (See"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23864, line : "Minucius Felix, Section 22.) Coleridge, Introd. p. 154, well"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23865, line : "observes, that the supreme father of gods and men had a full right"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23866, line : "to employ a lying spirit to work out his ultimate will. Compare"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23867, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" v. 646:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23869, line : "\"And roseate dews disposed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23870, line : "All but the unsleeping eyes of God to rest.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23872, line : "77 --_Dream_ ought to be spelt with a capital letter, being, I think,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23873, line : "evidently personified as the god of dreams. See Anthon and others."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23875, line : "\"When, by Minerva sent, a _fraudful_ Dream"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23876, line : "Rush'd from the skies, the bane of her and Troy.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23878, line : "Dyce's \"Select Translations from Quintus Calaber,\" p.10."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23880, line : "78 \"Sleep'st thou, companion dear, what sleep can close"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23881, line : "Thy eye-lids?\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23883, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" v. 673."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23885, line : "79 This truly military sentiment has been echoed by the approving voice"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23886, line : "of many a general and statesman of antiquity. See Pliny's Panegyric"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23887, line : "on Trajan. Silius neatly translates it,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23890, line : "\"Turpe duci totam somno consumere noctem.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23893, line : "80 --_The same in habit, &c._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23895, line : "\"To whom once more the winged god appears;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23896, line : "His former youthful mien and shape he wears.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23898, line : "Dryden's Virgil, iv. 803."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23900, line : "81 \"As bees in spring-time, when"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23901, line : "The sun with Taurus rides,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23902, line : "Pour forth their populous youth about the hive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23903, line : "In clusters; they among fresh dews and flowers"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23904, line : "Fly to and fro, or on the smoothed plank,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23905, line : "The suburb of this straw-built citadel,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23906, line : "New-nibb'd with balm, expatiate and confer"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23907, line : "Their state affairs. So thick the very crowd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23908, line : "Swarm'd and were straiten'd.\"--\"Paradise Lost\" i. 768."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23910, line : "82 It was the herald's duty to make the people sit down. \"A _standing_"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23911, line : "agora is a symptom of manifest terror (II. Xviii. 246) an evening"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23912, line : "agora, to which men came elevated by wine, is also the forerunner of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23913, line : "mischief ('Odyssey,' iii. 138).\"--Grote, ii. p. 91, _note._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23915, line : "83 This sceptre, like that of Judah (Genesis xlix. 10), is a type of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23916, line : "the supreme and far-spread dominion of the house of the Atrides. See"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23917, line : "Thucydides i. 9. \"It is traced through the hands of Hermes, he being"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23918, line : "the wealth giving god, whose blessing is most efficacious in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23919, line : "furthering the process of acquisition.\"--Grote, i. p. 212. Compare"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23920, line : "Quintus Calaber (Dyce's Selections, p. 43)."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23922, line : "\"Thus the monarch spoke,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23923, line : "Then pledged the chief in a capacious cup,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23924, line : "Golden, and framed by art divine (a gift"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23925, line : "Which to Almighty Jove lame Vulcan brought"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23926, line : "Upon his nuptial day, when he espoused"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23927, line : "The Queen of Love), the sire of gods bestow'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23928, line : "The cup on Dardanus, who gave it next"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23929, line : "To Ericthonius Tros received it then,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23930, line : "And left it, with his wealth, to be possess'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23931, line : "By Ilus he to great Laomedon"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23932, line : "Gave it, and last to Priam's lot it fell.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23934, line : "84 Grote, i, p. 393, states the number of the Grecian forces at upwards"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23935, line : "of 100,000 men. Nichols makes a total of 135,000."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23937, line : "85 \"As thick as when a field"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23938, line : "Of Ceres, ripe for harvest, waving bends"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23939, line : "His bearded grove of ears, which way the wind"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23940, line : "Sways them.\"--Paradise Lost,\" iv. 980, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23942, line : "86 This sentiment used to be a popular one with some of the greatest"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23943, line : "tyrants, who abused it into a pretext for unlimited usurpation of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23944, line : "power. Dion, Caligula, and Domitian were particularly fond of it,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23945, line : "and, in an extended form, we find the maxim propounded by Creon in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23946, line : "the Antigone of Sophocles. See some important remarks of Heeren,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23947, line : "\"Ancient Greece,\" ch. vi. p. 105."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23949, line : "87 It may be remarked, that the character of Thersites, revolting and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23950, line : "contemptible as it is, serves admirably to develop the disposition"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23951, line : "of Ulysses in a new light, in which mere cunning is less prominent."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23952, line : "Of the gradual and individual development of Homer's heroes,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23953, line : "Schlegel well observes, \"In bas-relief the figures are usually in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23954, line : "profile, and in the epos all are characterized in the simplest"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23955, line : "manner in relief; they are not grouped together, but follow one"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23956, line : "another; so Homer's heroes advance, one by one, in succession before"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23957, line : "us. It has been remarked that the _Iliad_ is not definitively"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23958, line : "closed, but that we are left to suppose something both to precede"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23959, line : "and to follow it. The bas-relief is equally without limit, and may"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23960, line : "be continued _ad infinitum,_ either from before or behind, on which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23961, line : "account the ancients preferred for it such subjects as admitted of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23962, line : "an indefinite extension, sacrificial processions, dances, and lines"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23963, line : "of combatants, and hence they also exhibit bas-reliefs on curved"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23964, line : "surfaces, such as vases, or the frieze of a rotunda, where, by the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23965, line : "curvature, the two ends are withdrawn from our sight, and where,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23966, line : "while we advance, one object appears as another disappears. Reading"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23967, line : "Homer is very much like such a circuit; the present object alone"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23968, line : "arresting our attention, we lose sight of what precedes, and do not"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23969, line : "concern ourselves about what is to follow.\"--\"Dramatic Literature,\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23970, line : "p. 75."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23972, line : "88 \"There cannot be a clearer indication than this description --so"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23973, line : "graphic in the original poem--of the true character of the Homeric"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23974, line : "agora. The multitude who compose it are listening and acquiescent,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23975, line : "not often hesitating, and never refractory to the chief. The fate"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23976, line : "which awaits a presumptuous critic, even where his virulent"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23977, line : "reproaches are substantially well-founded, is plainly set forth in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23978, line : "the treatment of Thersites; while the unpopularity of such a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23979, line : "character is attested even more by the excessive pains which Homer"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23980, line : "takes to heap upon him repulsive personal deformities, than by the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23981, line : "chastisement of Odysseus he is lame, bald, crook-backed, of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23982, line : "misshapen head, and squinting vision.\"--Grote, vol. i. p. 97."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23984, line : "89 According to Pausanias, both the sprig and the remains of the tree"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23985, line : "were exhibited in his time. The tragedians, Lucretius and others,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23986, line : "adopted a different fable to account for the stoppage at Aulis, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23987, line : "seem to have found the sacrifice of Iphigena better suited to form"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23988, line : "the subject of a tragedy. Compare Dryden's \"Ćneid,\" vol. iii. sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23990, line : "90 --_Full of his god, i.e.,_ Apollo, filled with the prophetic spirit."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23991, line : "\"_The_ god\" would be more simple and emphatic."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23993, line : "91 Those critics who have maintained that the \"Catalogue of Ships\" is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23994, line : "an interpolation, should have paid more attention to these lines,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23995, line : "which form a most natural introduction to their enumeration."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23997, line : "92 The following observation will be useful to Homeric readers:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23998, line : "\"Particular animals were, at a later time, consecrated to particular"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 23999, line : "deities. To Jupiter, Ceres, Juno, Apollo, and Bacchus victims of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24000, line : "advanced age might be offered. An ox of five years old was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24001, line : "considered especially acceptable to Jupiter. A black bull, a ram, or"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24002, line : "a boar pig, were offerings for Neptune. A heifer, or a sheep, for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24003, line : "Minerva. To Ceres a sow was sacrificed, as an enemy to corn. The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24004, line : "goat to Bacchus, because he fed on vines. Diana was propitiated with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24005, line : "a stag; and to Venus the dove was consecrated. The infernal and evil"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24006, line : "deities were to be appeased with black victims. The most acceptable"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24007, line : "of all sacrifices was the heifer of a year old, which had never"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24008, line : "borne the yoke. It was to be perfect in every limb, healthy, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24009, line : "without blemish.\"--\"Elgin Marbles,\" vol. i. p. 78."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24011, line : "93 --_Idomeneus,_ son of Deucalion, was king of Crete. Having vowed,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24012, line : "during a tempest, on his return from Troy, to sacrifice to Neptune"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24013, line : "the first creature that should present itself to his eye on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24014, line : "Cretan shore, his son fell a victim to his rash vow."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24016, line : "94 --_Tydeus' son, i.e._ Diomed."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24018, line : "95 That is, Ajax, the son of Oileus, a Locrian. He must be"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24019, line : "distinguished from the other, who was king of Salamis."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24021, line : "96 A great deal of nonsense has been written to account for the word"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24022, line : "_unbid,_ in this line. Even Plato, \"Sympos.\" p. 315, has found some"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24023, line : "curious meaning in what, to us, appears to need no explanation. Was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24024, line : "there any _heroic_ rule of etiquette which prevented one"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24025, line : "brother-king visiting another without a formal invitation?"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24027, line : "97 Fresh water fowl, especially swans, were found in great numbers"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24028, line : "about the Asian Marsh, a fenny tract of country in Lydia, formed by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24029, line : "the river Cayster, near its mouth. See Virgil, \"Georgics,\" vol. i."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24030, line : "383, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24032, line : "98 --_Scamander,_ or Scamandros, was a river of Troas, rising, according"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24033, line : "to Strabo, on the highest part of Mount Ida, in the same hill with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24034, line : "the Granicus and the OEdipus, and falling into the sea at Sigaeum;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24035, line : "everything tends to identify it with Mendere, as Wood, Rennell, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24036, line : "others maintain; the Mendere is 40 miles long, 300 feet broad, deep"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24037, line : "in the time of flood, nearly dry in the summer. Dr. Clarke"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24038, line : "successfully combats the opinion of those who make the Scamander to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24039, line : "have arisen from the springs of Bounabarshy, and traces the source"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24040, line : "of the river to the highest mountain in the chain of Ida, now"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24041, line : "Kusdaghy; receives the Simois in its course; towards its mouth it is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24042, line : "very muddy, and flows through marshes. Between the Scamander and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24043, line : "Simois, Homer's Troy is supposed to have stood: this river,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24044, line : "according to Homer, was called Xanthus by the gods, Scamander by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24045, line : "men. The waters of the Scamander had the singular property of giving"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24046, line : "a beautiful colour to the hair or wool of such animals as bathed in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24047, line : "them; hence the three goddesses, Minerva, Juno, and Venus, bathed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24048, line : "there before they appeared before Paris to obtain the golden apple:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24049, line : "the name Xanthus, \"yellow,\" was given to the Scamander, from the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24050, line : "peculiar colour of its waters, still applicable to the Mendere, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24051, line : "yellow colour of whose waters attracts the attention of travellers."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24053, line : "99 It should be \"his _chest_ like Neptune.\" The torso of Neptune, in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24054, line : "the \"Elgin Marbles,\" No. 103, (vol. ii. p. 26,) is remarkable for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24055, line : "its breadth and massiveness of development."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24057, line : "100 \"Say first, for heav'n hides nothing from thy view.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24059, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" i. 27."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24061, line : "\"Ma di' tu, Musa, come i primi danni"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24062, line : "Mandassero a Cristiani, e di quai parti:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24063, line : "Tu 'l sai; ma di tant' opra a noi si lunge"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24064, line : "Debil aura di fama appena giunge.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24066, line : "--\"Gier. Lib.\" iv. 19."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24068, line : "101 \"The Catalogue is, perhaps, the portion of the poem in favour of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24069, line : "which a claim to separate authorship has been most plausibly urged."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24070, line : "Although the example of Homer has since rendered some such formal"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24071, line : "enumeration of the forces engaged, a common practice in epic poems"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24072, line : "descriptive of great warlike adventures, still so minute a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24073, line : "statistical detail can neither be considered as imperatively"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24074, line : "required, nor perhaps such as would, in ordinary cases, suggest"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24075, line : "itself to the mind of a poet. Yet there is scarcely any portion of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24076, line : "the Iliad where both historical and internal evidence are more"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24077, line : "clearly in favour of a connection from the remotest period, with the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24078, line : "remainder of the work. The composition of the Catalogue, whensoever"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24079, line : "it may have taken place, necessarily presumes its author's"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24080, line : "acquaintance with a previously existing Iliad. It were impossible"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24081, line : "otherwise to account for the harmony observable in the recurrence of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24082, line : "so vast a number of proper names, most of them historically"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24083, line : "unimportant, and not a few altogether fictitious: or of so many"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24084, line : "geographical and genealogical details as are condensed in these few"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24085, line : "hundred lines, and incidentally scattered over the thousands which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24086, line : "follow: equally inexplicable were the pointed allusions occurring in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24087, line : "this episode to events narrated in the previous and subsequent text,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24088, line : "several of which could hardly be of traditional notoriety, but"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24089, line : "through the medium of the Iliad.\"--Mure, \"Language and Literature of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24090, line : "Greece,\" vol. i. p. 263."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24092, line : "102 --_Twice Sixty:_ \"Thucydides observes that the Boeotian vessels,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24093, line : "which carried one hundred and twenty men each, were probably meant"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24094, line : "to be the largest in the fleet, and those of Philoctetes, carrying"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24095, line : "fifty each, the smallest. The average would be eighty-five, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24096, line : "Thucydides supposes the troops to have rowed and navigated"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24097, line : "themselves; and that very few, besides the chiefs, went as mere"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24098, line : "passengers or landsmen. In short, we have in the Homeric"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24099, line : "descriptions the complete picture of an Indian or African war canoe,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24100, line : "many of which are considerably larger than the largest scale"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24101, line : "assigned to those of the Greeks. If the total number of the Greek"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24102, line : "ships be taken at twelve hundred, according to Thucydides, although"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24103, line : "in point of fact there are only eleven hundred and eighty-six in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24104, line : "Catalogue, the amount of the army, upon the foregoing average, will"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24105, line : "be about a hundred and two thousand men. The historian considers"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24106, line : "this a small force as representing all Greece. Bryant, comparing it"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24107, line : "with the allied army at Platae, thinks it so large as to prove the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24108, line : "entire falsehood of the whole story; and his reasonings and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24109, line : "calculations are, for their curiosity, well worth a careful"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24110, line : "perusal.\"--Coleridge, p. 211, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24112, line : "103 The mention of Corinth is an anachronism, as that city was called"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24113, line : "Ephyre before its capture by the Dorians. But Velleius, vol. i. p."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24114, line : "3, well observes, that the poet would naturally speak of various"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24115, line : "towns and cities by the names by which they were known in his own"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24116, line : "time."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24118, line : "104 \"Adam, the goodliest man of men since born,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24119, line : "His sons, the fairest of her daughters Eve.'"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24121, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" iv. 323."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24123, line : "105 --_Ćsetes' tomb._ Monuments were often built on the sea-coast, and of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24124, line : "a considerable height, so as to serve as watch-towers or land marks."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24125, line : "See my notes to my prose translations of the \"Odyssey,\" ii. p. 21,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24126, line : "or on Eur. \"Alcest.\" vol. i. p. 240."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24128, line : "106 --_Zeleia,_ another name for Lycia. The inhabitants were greatly"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24129, line : "devoted to the worship of Apollo. See Muller, \"Dorians,\" vol. i. p."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24130, line : "248."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24132, line : "107 --_Barbarous tongues._ \"Various as were the dialects of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24133, line : "Greeks--and these differences existed not only between the several"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24134, line : "tribes, but even between neighbouring cities--they yet acknowledged"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24135, line : "in their language that they formed but one nation were but branches"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24136, line : "of the same family. Homer has 'men of other tongues:' and yet Homer"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24137, line : "had no general name for the Greek nation.\"--Heeren, \"Ancient Greece,\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24138, line : "Section vii. p. 107, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24140, line : "_  108 The cranes._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24141, line : "\"Marking the tracts of air, the clamorous cranes"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24142, line : "Wheel their due flight in varied ranks descried:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24143, line : "And each with outstretch'd neck his rank maintains,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24144, line : "In marshall'd order through th' ethereal void.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24146, line : "Lorenzo de Medici, in Roscoe's Life, Appendix."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24148, line : "See Cary's Dante: \"Hell,\" canto v."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24150, line : "_  109 Silent, breathing rage._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24151, line : "\"Thus they,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24152, line : "Breathing united force with fixed thought,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24153, line : "Moved on in silence.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24155, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" book i. 559."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24157, line : "110 \"As when some peasant in a bushy brake"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24158, line : "Has with unwary footing press'd a snake;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24159, line : "He starts aside, astonish'd, when he spies"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24160, line : "His rising crest, blue neck, and rolling eyes\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24162, line : "Dryden's Virgil, ii. 510."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24164, line : "111 Dysparis, i.e. unlucky, ill fated, Paris. This alludes to the evils"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24165, line : "which resulted from his having been brought up, despite the omens"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24166, line : "which attended his birth."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24168, line : "112 The following scene, in which Homer has contrived to introduce so"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24169, line : "brilliant a sketch of the Grecian warriors, has been imitated by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24170, line : "Euripides, who in his \"Phoenissae\" represents Antigone surveying the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24171, line : "opposing champions from a high tower, while the paedagogus describes"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24172, line : "their insignia and details their histories."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24174, line : "113 --_No wonder,_ &c. Zeuxis, the celebrated artist, is said to have"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24175, line : "appended these lines to his picture of Helen, as a motto. Valer Max."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24176, line : "iii. 7."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24178, line : "114 The early epic was largely occupied with the exploits and sufferings"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24179, line : "of women, or heroines, the wives and daughters of the Grecian"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24180, line : "heroes. A nation of courageous, hardy, indefatigable women, dwelling"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24181, line : "apart from men, permitting only a short temporary intercourse, for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24182, line : "the purpose of renovating their numbers, burning out their right"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24183, line : "breast with a view of enabling themselves to draw the bow freely;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24184, line : "this was at once a general type, stimulating to the fancy of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24185, line : "poet, and a theme eminently popular with his hearers. We find these"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24186, line : "warlike females constantly reappearing in the ancient poems, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24187, line : "universally accepted as past realities in the Iliad. When Priam"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24188, line : "wishes to illustrate emphatically the most numerous host in which he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24189, line : "ever found himself included, he tells us that it was assembled in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24190, line : "Phrygia, on the banks of the Sangarius, for the purpose of resisting"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24191, line : "the formidable Amazons. When Bellerophon is to be employed in a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24192, line : "deadly and perilous undertaking, by those who prudently wished to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24193, line : "procure his death, he is despatched against the Amazons.--Grote, vol."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24194, line : "i p. 289."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24196, line : "115 --_Antenor,_ like Ćneas, had always been favourable to the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24197, line : "restoration of Helen. Liv 1. 2."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24199, line : "116 \"His lab'ring heart with sudden rapture seized"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24200, line : "He paus'd, and on the ground in silence gazed."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24201, line : "Unskill'd and uninspired he seems to stand,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24202, line : "Nor lifts the eye, nor graceful moves the hand:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24203, line : "Then, while the chiefs in still attention hung,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24204, line : "Pours the full tide of eloquence along;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24205, line : "While from his lips the melting torrent flows,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24206, line : "Soft as the fleeces of descending snows."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24207, line : "Now stronger notes engage the listening crowd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24208, line : "Louder the accents rise, and yet more loud,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24209, line : "Like thunders rolling from a distant cloud.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24211, line : "Merrick's \"Tryphiodorus,\" 148, 99."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24213, line : "117 Duport, \"Gnomol. Homer,\" p. 20, well observes that this comparison"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24214, line : "may also be sarcastically applied to the _frigid_ style of oratory."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24215, line : "It, of course, here merely denotes the ready fluency of Ulysses."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24217, line : "118 --_Her brothers' doom._ They perished in combat with Lynceus and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24218, line : "Idas, whilst besieging Sparta. See Hygin. Poet Astr. 32, 22. Virgil"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24219, line : "and others, however, make them share immortality by turns."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24221, line : "119 Idreus was the arm-bearer and charioteer of king Priam, slain during"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24222, line : "this war. Cf. Ćn, vi. 487."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24224, line : "120 --_Scaea's gates,_ rather _Scaean gates,_ _i.e._ the left-hand gates."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24226, line : "121 This was customary in all sacrifices. Hence we find Iras descending"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24227, line : "to cut off the hair of Dido, before which she could not expire."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24229, line : "122 --_Nor pierced._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24231, line : "\"This said, his feeble hand a jav'lin threw,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24232, line : "Which, flutt'ring, seemed to loiter as it flew,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24233, line : "Just, and but barely, to the mark it held,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24234, line : "And faintly tinkled on the brazen shield.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24236, line : "Dryden's Virgil, ii. 742."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24238, line : "_  123 Reveal'd the queen._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24240, line : "\"Thus having said, she turn'd and made appear"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24241, line : "Her neck refulgent and dishevell'd hair,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24242, line : "Which, flowing from her shoulders, reach'd the ground,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24243, line : "And widely spread ambrosial scents around."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24244, line : "In length of train descends her sweeping gown;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24245, line : "And, by her graceful walk, the queen of love is known.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24247, line : "Dryden's Virgil, i. 556."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24249, line : "124 --_Cranae's isle, i.e._ Athens. See the \"Schol.\" and Alberti's"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24250, line : "\"Hesychius,\" vol. ii. p. 338. This name was derived from one of its"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24251, line : "early kings, Cranaus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24253, line : "125 --_The martial maid._ In the original, \"Minerva Alalcomeneis,\" _i.e."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24254, line : "the defender,_ so called from her temple at Alalcomene in Boeotia."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24256, line : "126 \"Anything for a quiet life!\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24258, line : "127 --_Argos._ The worship of Juno at Argos was very celebrated in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24259, line : "ancient times, and she was regarded as the patron deity of that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24260, line : "city. Apul. Met., vi. p. 453; Servius on Virg. Ćn., i. 28."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24262, line : "128 --_A wife and sister._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24264, line : "\"But I, who walk in awful state above"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24265, line : "The majesty of heav'n, the sister-wife of Jove.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24267, line : "Dryden's \"Virgil,\" i. 70."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24269, line : "So Apuleius, _l. c._ speaks of her as \"Jovis germana et conjux, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24270, line : "so Horace, Od. iii. 3, 64, \"conjuge me Jovis et sorore.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24272, line : "129 \"Thither came Uriel, gleaming through the even"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24273, line : "On a sunbeam, swift as a shooting star"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24274, line : "In autumn thwarts the night, when vapours fired"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24275, line : "Impress the air, and shows the mariner"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24276, line : "From what point of his compass to beware"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24277, line : "Impetuous winds.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24279, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" iv. 555."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24281, line : "130 --_Ćsepus' flood._ A river of Mysia, rising from Mount Cotyius, in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24282, line : "the southern part of the chain of Ida."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24284, line : "131 --_Zelia,_ a town of Troas, at the foot of Ida."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24286, line : "132 --_Podaleirius_ and _Machaon_ are the leeches of the Grecian army,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24287, line : "highly prized and consulted by all the wounded chiefs. Their medical"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24288, line : "renown was further prolonged in the subsequent poem of Arktinus, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24289, line : "Iliou Persis, wherein the one was represented as unrivalled in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24290, line : "surgical operations, the other as sagacious in detecting and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24291, line : "appreciating morbid symptoms. It was Podaleirius who first noticed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24292, line : "the glaring eyes and disturbed deportment which preceded the suicide"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24293, line : "of Ajax."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24295, line : "\"Galen appears uncertain whether Asklepius (as well as Dionysus) was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24296, line : "originally a god, or whether he was first a man and then became"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24297, line : "afterwards a god; but Apollodorus professed to fix the exact date of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24298, line : "his apotheosis. Throughout all the historical ages the descendants"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24299, line : "of Asklepius were numerous and widely diffused. The many families or"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24300, line : "gentes, called Asklepiads, who devoted themselves to the study and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24301, line : "practice of medicine, and who principally dwelt near the temples of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24302, line : "Asklepius, whither sick and suffering men came to obtain relief--all"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24303, line : "recognized the god not merely as the object of their common worship,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24304, line : "but also as their actual progenitor.\"--Grote vol. i. p. 248."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24306, line : "133 \"The plant she bruises with a stone, and stands"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24307, line : "Tempering the juice between her ivory hands"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24308, line : "This o'er her breast she sheds with sovereign art"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24309, line : "And bathes with gentle touch the wounded part"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24310, line : "The wound such virtue from the juice derives,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24311, line : "At once the blood is stanch'd, the youth revives.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24313, line : "\"Orlando Furioso,\"  book 1."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24315, line : "134 --_Well might I wish._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24317, line : "\"Would heav'n (said he) my strength and youth recall,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24318, line : "Such as I was beneath Praeneste's wall--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24319, line : "Then when I made the foremost foes retire,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24320, line : "And set whole heaps of conquer'd shields on fire;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24321, line : "When Herilus in single fight I slew,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24322, line : "Whom with three lives Feronia did endue.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24324, line : "Dryden's Virgil, viii. 742."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24326, line : "135 --_Sthenelus,_ a son of Capaneus, one of the Epigoni. He was one of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24327, line : "the suitors of Helen, and is said to have been one of those who"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24328, line : "entered Troy inside the wooden horse."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24330, line : "136 --_Forwarn'd the horrors._ The same portent has already been"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24331, line : "mentioned. To this day, modern nations are not wholly free from this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24332, line : "superstition."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24334, line : "137 --_Sevenfold city,_ Boeotian Thebes, which had seven gates."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24336, line : "138 --_As when the winds._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24338, line : "\"Thus, when a black-brow'd gust begins to rise,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24339, line : "White foam at first on the curl'd ocean fries;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24340, line : "Then roars the main, the billows mount the skies,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24341, line : "Till, by the fury of the storm full blown,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24342, line : "The muddy billow o'er the clouds is thrown.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24344, line : "Dryden's Virgil, vii. 736."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24346, line : "139 \"Stood"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24347, line : "Like Teneriffe or Atlas unremoved;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24348, line : "His stature reach'd the sky.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24350, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" iv. 986."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24352, line : "140 The Abantes seem to have been of Thracian origin."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24354, line : "141 I may, once for all, remark that Homer is most anatomically correct"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24355, line : "as to the parts of the body in which a wound would be immediately"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24356, line : "mortal."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24358, line : "142 --_Ćnus,_ a fountain almost proverbial for its coldness."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24360, line : "143 Compare Tasso, Gier. Lib., xx. 7:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24362, line : "\"Nuovo favor del cielo in lui niluce"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24363, line : "E 'l fa grande, et angusto oltre il costume."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24364, line : "Gl' empie d' honor la faccia, e vi riduce"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24365, line : "Di giovinezza il bel purpureo lume.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24367, line : "144 \"Or deluges, descending on the plains,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24368, line : "Sweep o'er the yellow year, destroy the pains"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24369, line : "Of lab'ring oxen, and the peasant's gains;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24370, line : "Uproot the forest oaks, and bear away"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24371, line : "Flocks, folds, and trees, an undistinguish'd prey.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24373, line : "Dryden's Virgil ii. 408."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24375, line : "145 --_From mortal mists._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24377, line : "\"But to nobler sights"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24378, line : "Michael from Adam's eyes the film removed.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24380, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" xi. 411."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24382, line : "146 --_The race of those._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24384, line : "\"A pair of coursers, born of heav'nly breed,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24385, line : "Who from their nostrils breathed ethereal fire;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24386, line : "Whom Circe stole from her celestial sire,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24387, line : "By substituting mares produced on earth,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24388, line : "Whose wombs conceived a more than mortal birth."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24390, line : "Dryden's Virgil, vii. 386, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24392, line : "147 The belief in the existence of men of larger stature in earlier"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24393, line : "times, is by no means confined to Homer."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24395, line : "148 --_Such stream, i.e._ the _ichor,_ or blood of the gods."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24397, line : "\"A stream of nect'rous humour issuing flow'd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24398, line : "Sanguine, such as celestial spirits may bleed.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24400, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 339."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24402, line : "149 This was during the wars with the Titans."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24404, line : "150 --_Amphitryon's son,_ Hercules, born to Jove by Alcmena, the wife of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24405, line : "Amphitryon."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24407, line : "151 --_Ćgiale_ daughter of Adrastus. The Cyclic poets (See Anthon's"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24408, line : "Lempriere, _s. v._) assert Venus incited her to infidelity, in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24409, line : "revenge for the wound she had received from her husband."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24411, line : "152 --_Pherae,_ a town of Pelasgiotis, in Thessaly."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24413, line : "153 --_Tlepolemus,_ son of Hercules and Astyochia. Having left his native"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24414, line : "country, Argos, in consequence of the accidental murder of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24415, line : "Liscymnius, he was commanded by an oracle to retire to Rhodes. Here"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24416, line : "he was chosen king, and accompanied the Trojan expedition. After his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24417, line : "death, certain games were instituted at Rhodes in his honour, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24418, line : "victors being rewarded with crowns of poplar."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24420, line : "154 These heroes' names have since passed into a kind of proverb,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24421, line : "designating the _oi polloi_ or mob."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24423, line : "155 --_Spontaneous open._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24425, line : "\"Veil'd with his gorgeous wings, upspringing light"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24426, line : "Flew through the midst of heaven; th' angelic quires,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24427, line : "On each hand parting, to his speed gave way"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24428, line : "Through all th' empyreal road; till at the gate"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24429, line : "Of heaven arrived, the gate self-open'd wide,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24430, line : "On golden hinges turning.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24432, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" v. 250."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24434, line : "156 \"Till Morn,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24435, line : "Waked by the circling Hours, with rosy hand"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24436, line : "Unbarr'd the gates of light.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24438, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi, 2."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24440, line : "157 --_Far as a shepherd._ \"With what majesty and pomp does Homer exalt"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24441, line : "his deities! He here measures the leap of the horses by the extent"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24442, line : "of the world. And who is there, that, considering the exceeding"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24443, line : "greatness of the space would not with reason cry out that 'If the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24444, line : "steeds of the deity were to take a second leap, the world would want"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24445, line : "room for it'?\"--Longinus, Section 8."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24447, line : "158 \"No trumpets, or any other instruments of sound, are used in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24448, line : "Homeric action itself; but the trumpet was known, and is introduced"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24449, line : "for the purpose of illustration as employed in war. Hence arose the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24450, line : "value of a loud voice in a commander; Stentor was an indispensable"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24451, line : "officer... In the early Saracen campaigns frequent mention is made"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24452, line : "of the service rendered by men of uncommonly strong voices; the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24453, line : "battle of Honain was restored by the shouts and menaces of Abbas,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24454, line : "the uncle of Mohammed,\" &c.--Coleridge, p. 213."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24456, line : "159 \"Long had the wav'ring god the war delay'd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24457, line : "While Greece and Troy alternate own'd his aid.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24459, line : "Merrick's \"Tryphiodorus,\" vi. 761, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24461, line : "160 --_Paeon_ seems to have been to the gods, what Podaleirius and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24462, line : "Machaon were to the Grecian heroes."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24464, line : "161 --_Arisbe,_ a colony of the Mitylenaeans in Troas."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24466, line : "162 --_Pedasus,_ a town near Pylos."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24468, line : "163 --_Rich heaps of brass._ \"The halls of Alkinous and Menelaus glitter"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24469, line : "with gold, copper, and electrum; while large stocks of yet"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24470, line : "unemployed metal--gold, copper, and iron are stored up in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24471, line : "treasure-chamber of Odysseus and other chiefs. Coined money is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24472, line : "unknown in the Homeric age--the trade carried on being one of barter."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24473, line : "In reference also to the metals, it deserves to be remarked, that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24474, line : "the Homeric descriptions universally suppose copper, and not iron,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24475, line : "to be employed for arms, both offensive and defensive. By what"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24476, line : "process the copper was tempered and hardened, so as to serve the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24477, line : "purpose of the warrior, we do not know; but the use of iron for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24478, line : "these objects belongs to a later age.\"--Grote, vol. ii. p. 142."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24480, line : "164 --_Oh impotent,_ &c. \"In battle, quarter seems never to have been"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24481, line : "given, except with a view to the ransom of the prisoner. Agamemnon"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24482, line : "reproaches Menelaus with unmanly softness, when he is on the point"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24483, line : "of sparing a fallen enemy, and himself puts the suppliant to the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24484, line : "sword.\"--Thirlwall, vol. i. p. 181"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24486, line : "165 \"The ruthless steel, impatient of delay,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24487, line : "Forbade the sire to linger out the day."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24488, line : "It struck the bending father to the earth,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24489, line : "And cropt the wailing infant at the birth."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24490, line : "Can innocents the rage of parties know,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24491, line : "And they who ne'er offended find a foe?\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24493, line : "Rowe's Lucan, bk. ii."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24495, line : "166 \"Meantime the Trojan dames, oppress'd with woe,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24496, line : "To Pallas' fane in long procession go,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24497, line : "In hopes to reconcile their heav'nly foe:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24498, line : "They weep; they beat their breasts; they rend their hair,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24499, line : "And rich embroider'd vests for presents bear.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24501, line : "Dryden's Virgil, i. 670"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24503, line : "167 The manner in which this episode is introduced, is well illustrated"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24504, line : "by the following remarks of Mure, vol. i. p.298: \"The poet's method"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24505, line : "of introducing his episode, also, illustrates in a curious manner"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24506, line : "his tact in the dramatic department of his art. Where, for example,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24507, line : "one or more heroes are despatched on some commission, to be executed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24508, line : "at a certain distance of time or place, the fulfilment of this task"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24509, line : "is not, as a general rule, immediately described. A certain interval"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24510, line : "is allowed them for reaching the appointed scene of action, which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24511, line : "interval is dramatised, as it were, either by a temporary"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24512, line : "continuation of the previous narrative, or by fixing attention for a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24513, line : "while on some new transaction, at the close of which the further"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24514, line : "account of the mission is resumed.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24516, line : "168 --_With tablets sealed._ These probably were only devices of a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24517, line : "hieroglyphical character. Whether writing was known in the Homeric"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24518, line : "times is utterly uncertain. See Grote, vol ii. p. 192, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24520, line : "169 --_Solymaean crew,_ a people of Lycia."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24522, line : "170 From this \"melancholy madness\" of Bellerophon, hypochondria received"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24523, line : "the name of \"Morbus Bellerophonteus.\" See my notes in my prose"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24524, line : "translation, p. 112. The \"Aleian field,\" _i.e._ \"the plain of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24525, line : "wandering,\" was situated between the rivers Pyramus and Pinarus, in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24526, line : "Cilicia."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24528, line : "171 --_His own, of gold._ This bad bargain has passed into a common"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24529, line : "proverb. See Aulus Gellius, ii, 23."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24531, line : "172 --_Scaean, i e._ left hand."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24533, line : "173 --_In fifty chambers._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24535, line : "\"The fifty nuptial beds, (such hopes had he,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24536, line : "So large a promise of a progeny,)"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24537, line : "The ports of plated gold, and hung with spoils.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24539, line : "Dryden's Virgil, ii.658"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24541, line : "174 --_O would kind earth,_ &c. \"It is apparently a sudden, irregular"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24542, line : "burst of popular indignation to which Hector alludes, when he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24543, line : "regrets that the Trojans had not spirit enough to cover Paris with a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24544, line : "mantle of stones. This, however, was also one of the ordinary formal"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24545, line : "modes of punishment for great public offences. It may have been"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24546, line : "originally connected with the same feeling--the desire of avoiding"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24547, line : "the pollution of bloodshed--which seems to have suggested the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24548, line : "practice of burying prisoners alive, with a scantling of food by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24549, line : "their side. Though Homer makes no mention of this horrible usage,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24550, line : "the example of the Roman Vestals affords reasons for believing that,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24551, line : "in ascribing it to the heroic ages, Sophocles followed an authentic"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24552, line : "tradition.\"--Thirlwall's Greece, vol. i. p. 171, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24554, line : "175 --_Paris' lofty dome._ \"With respect to the private dwellings, which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24555, line : "are oftenest described, the poet's language barely enables us to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24556, line : "form a general notion of their ordinary plan, and affords no"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24557, line : "conception of the style which prevailed in them or of their effect"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24558, line : "on the eye. It seems indeed probable, from the manner in which he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24559, line : "dwells on their metallic ornaments that the higher beauty of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24560, line : "proportion was but little required or understood, and it is,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24561, line : "perhaps, strength and convenience, rather than elegance, that he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24562, line : "means to commend, in speaking of the fair house which Paris had"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24563, line : "built for himself with the aid of the most skilful masons of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24564, line : "Troy.\"--Thirlwall's Greece, vol. i. p. 231."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24566, line : "176 --_The wanton courser._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24568, line : "\"Come destrier, che da le regie stalle"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24569, line : "Ove a l'usa de l'arme si riserba,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24570, line : "Fugge, e libero al fiu per largo calle"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24571, line : "Va tragl' armenti, o al fiume usato, o a l'herba.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24573, line : "Gier, Lib. ix. 75."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24575, line : "177 --_Casque._ The original word is stephanae, about the meaning of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24576, line : "which there is some little doubt. Some take it for a different kind"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24577, line : "of cap or helmet, others for the rim, others for the cone, of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24578, line : "helmet."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24580, line : "178 --_Athenian maid:_ Minerva."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24582, line : "179 --_Celadon,_ a river of Elis."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24584, line : "180 --_Oileus, i.e._ Ajax, the son of Oileus, in contradistinction to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24585, line : "Ajax, son of Telamon."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24587, line : "181 --_In the general's helm._ It was customary to put the lots into a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24588, line : "helmet, in which they were well shaken up; each man then took his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24589, line : "choice."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24591, line : "182 --_God of Thrace._ Mars, or Mavors, according to his Thracian"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24592, line : "epithet. Hence \"Mavortia Moenia.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24594, line : "183 --_Grimly he smiled._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24596, line : "\"And death"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24597, line : "Grinn'd horribly a ghastly smile.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24599, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" ii. 845."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24601, line : "\"There Mavors stands"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24602, line : "Grinning with ghastly feature.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24604, line : "--Carey's Dante: Hell, v."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24606, line : "184 \"Sete o guerrieri, incomincio Pindoro,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24607, line : "Con pari honor di pari ambo possenti,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24608, line : "Dunque cessi la pugna, e non sian rotte"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24609, line : "Le ragioni, e 'l riposo, e de la notte.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24611, line : "--Gier. Lib. vi. 51."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24613, line : "185 It was an ancient style of compliment to give a larger portion of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24614, line : "food to the conqueror, or person to whom respect was to be shown."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24615, line : "See Virg. Ćn. viii. 181. Thus Benjamin was honoured with a \"double"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24616, line : "portion.\" Gen. xliii. 34."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24618, line : "186 --_Embattled walls._ \"Another essential basis of mechanical unity in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24619, line : "the poem is the construction of the rampart. This takes place in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24620, line : "seventh book. The reason ascribed for the glaring improbability that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24621, line : "the Greeks should have left their camp and fleet unfortified during"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24622, line : "nine years, in the midst of a hostile country, is a purely poetical"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24623, line : "one: 'So long as Achilles fought, the terror of his name sufficed to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24624, line : "keep every foe at a distance.' The disasters consequent on his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24625, line : "secession first led to the necessity of other means of protection."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24626, line : "Accordingly, in the battles previous to the eighth book, no allusion"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24627, line : "occurs to a rampart; in all those which follow it forms a prominent"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24628, line : "feature. Here, then, in the anomaly as in the propriety of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24629, line : "Iliad, the destiny of Achilles, or rather this peculiar crisis of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24630, line : "it, forms the pervading bond of connexion to the whole poem.\"--Mure,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24631, line : "vol. i., p. 257."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24633, line : "187 --_What cause of fear,_ &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24635, line : "\"Seest thou not this? Or do we fear in vain"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24636, line : "Thy boasted thunders, and thy thoughtless reign?\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24638, line : "Dryden's Virgil, iv. 304."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24640, line : "188 --_In exchange._ These lines are referred to by Theophilus, the Roman"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24641, line : "lawyer, iii. tit. xxiii. Section 1, as exhibiting the most ancient"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24642, line : "mention of barter."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24644, line : "189 \"A similar bond of connexion, in the military details of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24645, line : "narrative, is the decree issued by Jupiter, at the commencement of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24646, line : "the eighth book, against any further interference of the gods in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24647, line : "battles. In the opening of the twentieth book this interdict is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24648, line : "withdrawn. During the twelve intermediate books it is kept steadily"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24649, line : "in view. No interposition takes place but on the part of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24650, line : "specially authorised agents of Jove, or on that of one or two"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24651, line : "contumacious deities, described as boldly setting his commands at"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24652, line : "defiance, but checked and reprimanded for their disobedience; while"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24653, line : "the other divine warriors, who in the previous and subsequent cantos"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24654, line : "are so active in support of their favourite heroes, repeatedly"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24655, line : "allude to the supreme edict as the cause of their present"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24656, line : "inactivity.\"--Mure, vol. i. p 257. See however, Muller, \"Greek"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24657, line : "Literature,\" ch. v. Section 6, and Grote, vol. ii. p. 252."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24659, line : "190 \"As far removed from God and light of heaven,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24660, line : "As from the centre thrice to th' utmost pole.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24662, line : "--\"Paradise Lost.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24664, line : "\"E quanto e da le stelle al basso inferno,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24665, line : "Tanto e piu in su de la stellata spera\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24667, line : "--Gier. Lib. i. 7."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24669, line : "\"Some of the epithets which Homer applies to the heavens seem to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24670, line : "imply that he considered it as a solid vault of metal. But it is not"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24671, line : "necessary to construe these epithets so literally, nor to draw any"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24672, line : "such inference from his description of Atlas, who holds the lofty"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24673, line : "pillars which keep earth and heaven asunder. Yet it would seem, from"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24674, line : "the manner in which the height of heaven is compared with the depth"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24675, line : "of Tartarus, that the region of light was thought to have certain"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24676, line : "bounds. The summit of the Thessalian Olympus was regarded as the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24677, line : "highest point on the earth, and it is not always carefully"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24678, line : "distinguished from the aerian regions above The idea of a seat of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24679, line : "the gods--perhaps derived from a more ancient tradition, in which it"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24680, line : "was not attached to any geographical site--seems to be indistinctly"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24681, line : "blended in the poet's mind with that of the real"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24682, line : "mountain.\"--Thirlwall's Greece, vol. i. p. 217, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24684, line : "191 \"Now lately heav'n, earth, another world"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24685, line : "Hung e'er my realm, link'd in a golden chain"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24686, line : "To that side heav'n.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24688, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" ii. 1004."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24690, line : "192 --_His golden scales._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24692, line : "\"Jove now, sole arbiter of peace and war,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24693, line : "Held forth the fatal balance from afar:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24694, line : "Each host he weighs; by turns they both prevail,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24695, line : "Till Troy descending fix'd the doubtful scale.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24697, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, v 687, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24699, line : "\"Th' Eternal, to prevent such horrid fray,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24700, line : "Hung forth in heav'n his golden scales,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24701, line : "Wherein all things created first he weighed;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24702, line : "The pendulous round earth, with balanced air"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24703, line : "In counterpoise; now ponders all events,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24704, line : "Battles and realms. In these he puts two weights,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24705, line : "The sequel each of parting and of fight:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24706, line : "The latter quick up flew, and kick'd the beam.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24708, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" iv. 496."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24710, line : "193 --_And now,_ &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24712, line : "\"And now all heaven"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24713, line : "Had gone to wrack, with ruin overspread;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24714, line : "Had not th' Almighty Father, where he sits"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24715, line : "... foreseen.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24717, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 669."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24719, line : "194 --_Gerenian Nestor._ The epithet _Gerenian_ either refers to the name"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24720, line : "of a place in which Nestor was educated, or merely signifies"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24721, line : "honoured, revered. See Schol. Venet. in II. B. 336; Strabo, viii. p."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24722, line : "340."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24724, line : "195 --_Ćgae, Helice._ Both these towns were conspicuous for their worship"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24725, line : "of Neptune."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24727, line : "196 --_As full blown,_ &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24729, line : "\"Il suo Lesbia quasi bel fior succiso,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24730, line : "E in atto si gentil languir tremanti"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24731, line : "Gl' occhi, e cader siu 'l tergo il collo mira.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24733, line : "Gier. Lib. ix. 85."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24735, line : "197 --_Ungrateful,_ because the cause in which they were engaged was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24736, line : "unjust."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24738, line : "\"Struck by the lab'ring priests' uplifted hands"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24739, line : "The victims fall: to heav'n they make their pray'r,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24740, line : "The curling vapours load the ambient air."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24741, line : "But vain their toil: the pow'rs who rule the skies"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24742, line : "Averse beheld the ungrateful sacrifice.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24744, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, vi. 527, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24746, line : "198 \"As when about the silver moon, when aire is free from"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24747, line : "winde,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24748, line : "And stars shine cleare, to whose sweet beams high prospects on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24749, line : "brows"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24750, line : "Of all steepe hills and pinnacles thrust up themselves for shows,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24751, line : "And even the lowly valleys joy to glitter in their sight;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24752, line : "When the unmeasured firmament bursts to disclose her light,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24753, line : "And all the signs in heaven are seene, that glad the shepherd's"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24754, line : "heart.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24756, line : "Chapman."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24758, line : "199 This flight of the Greeks, according to Buttmann, Lexil. p. 358, was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24759, line : "not a supernatural flight caused by the gods, but \"a great and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24760, line : "general one, caused by Hector and the Trojans, but with the approval"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24761, line : "of Jove.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24763, line : "200 Grote, vol. ii. p. 91, after noticing the modest calmness and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24764, line : "respect with which Nestor addresses Agamemnon, observes, \"The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24765, line : "Homeric Council is a purely consultative body, assembled not with"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24766, line : "any power of peremptorily arresting mischievous resolves of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24767, line : "king, but solely for his information and guidance.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24769, line : "201 In the heroic times, it is not unfrequent for the king to receive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24770, line : "presents to purchase freedom from his wrath, or immunity from his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24771, line : "exactions. Such gifts gradually became regular, and formed the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24772, line : "income of the German, (Tacit. Germ. Section 15) Persian, (Herodot."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24773, line : "iii.89), and other kings. So, too, in the middle ages, 'The feudal"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24774, line : "aids are the beginning of taxation, of which they for a long time"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24775, line : "answered the purpose.' (Hallam, Middle Ages, ch. x. pt. 1, p. 189)"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24776, line : "This fact frees Achilles from the apparent charge of sordidness."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24777, line : "Plato, however, (De Rep. vi. 4), says, \"We cannot commend Phoenix,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24778, line : "the tutor of Achilles, as if he spoke correctly, when counselling"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24779, line : "him to accept of presents and assist the Greeks, but, without"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24780, line : "presents, not to desist from his wrath, nor again, should we commend"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24781, line : "Achilles himself, or approve of his being so covetous as to receive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24782, line : "presents from Agamemnon,\" &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24784, line : "202 It may be observed, that, brief as is the mention of Briseis in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24785, line : "Iliad, and small the part she plays--what little is said is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24786, line : "pre-eminently calculated to enhance her fitness to be the bride of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24787, line : "Achilles. Purity, and retiring delicacy, are features well"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24788, line : "contrasted with the rough, but tender disposition of the hero."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24790, line : "203 --_Laodice._ Iphianassa, or Iphigenia, is not mentioned by Homer,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24791, line : "among the daughters of Agamemnon."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24793, line : "204 \"Agamemnon, when he offers to transfer to Achilles seven towns"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24794, line : "inhabited by wealthy husbandmen, who would enrich their lord by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24795, line : "presents and tribute, seems likewise to assume rather a property in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24796, line : "them, than an authority over them. And the same thing may be"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24797, line : "intimated when it is said that Peleus bestowed a great people, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24798, line : "Dolopes of Phthia, on Phoenix.\"--Thirlwall's Greece, vol. i Section"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24799, line : "6, p. 162, note."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24801, line : "205 --_Pray in deep silence._ Rather: \"use well-omened words;\" or, as"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24802, line : "Kennedy has explained it, \"Abstain from expressions unsuitable to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24803, line : "the solemnity of the occasion, which, by offending the god, might"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24804, line : "defeat the object of their supplications.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24806, line : "206 --_Purest hands._ This is one of the most ancient superstitions"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24807, line : "respecting prayer, and one founded as much in nature as in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24808, line : "tradition."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24810, line : "207 It must be recollected, that the war at Troy was not a settled"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24811, line : "siege, and that many of the chieftains busied themselves in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24812, line : "piratical expeditions about its neighborhood. Such a one was that of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24813, line : "which Achilles now speaks. From the following verses, it is evident"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24814, line : "that fruits of these maraudings went to the common support of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24815, line : "expedition, and not to the successful plunderer."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24817, line : "208 --_Pthia,_ the capital of Achilles' Thessalian domains."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24819, line : "209 --_Orchomenian town._ The topography of Orchomenus, in Boeotia,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24820, line : "\"situated,\" as it was, \"on the northern bank of the lake Ćpais,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24821, line : "which receives not only the river Cephisus from the valleys of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24822, line : "Phocis, but also other rivers from Parnassus and Helicon\" (Grote,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24823, line : "vol. p. 181), was a sufficient reason for its prosperity and decay."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24824, line : "\"As long as the channels of these waters were diligently watched and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24825, line : "kept clear, a large portion of the lake was in the condition of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24826, line : "alluvial land, pre-eminently rich and fertile. But when the channels"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24827, line : "came to be either neglected, or designedly choked up by an enemy,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24828, line : "the water accumulated in such a degree as to occupy the soil of more"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24829, line : "than one ancient islet, and to occasion the change of the site of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24830, line : "Orchomenus itself from the plain to the declivity of Mount"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24831, line : "Hyphanteion.\" (Ibid.)"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24833, line : "210 The phrase \"hundred gates,\" &c., seems to be merely expressive of a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24834, line : "great number. See notes to my prose translation, p. 162."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24836, line : "211 Compare the following pretty lines of Quintus Calaber (Dyce's Select"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24837, line : "Translations, p 88).--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24839, line : "\"Many gifts he gave, and o'er"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24840, line : "Dolopia bade me rule; thee in his arms"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24841, line : "He brought an infant, on my bosom laid"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24842, line : "The precious charge, and anxiously enjoin'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24843, line : "That I should rear thee as my own with all"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24844, line : "A parent's love. I fail'd not in my trust"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24845, line : "And oft, while round my neck thy hands were lock'd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24846, line : "From thy sweet lips the half articulate sound"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24847, line : "Of Father came; and oft, as children use,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24848, line : "Mewling and puking didst thou drench my tunic.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24850, line : "\"This description,\" observes my learned friend (notes, p. 121) \"is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24851, line : "taken from the passage of Homer, II ix, in translating which, Pope,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24852, line : "with that squeamish, artificial taste, which distinguished the age"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24853, line : "of Anne, omits the natural (and, let me add, affecting)"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24854, line : "circumstance.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24856, line : "\"And the wine"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24857, line : "Held to thy lips, and many a time in fits"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24858, line : "Of infant frowardness the purple juice"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24859, line : "Rejecting thou hast deluged all my vest,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24860, line : "And fill'd my bosom.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24862, line : "--Cowper."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24864, line : "212 --_Where Calydon._ For a good sketch of the story of Meleager, too"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24865, line : "long to be inserted here, see Grote, vol. i. p. 195, sqq.; and for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24866, line : "the authorities, see my notes to the prose translation, p. 166."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24868, line : "213 \"_Gifts can conquer_\"--It is well observed by Bishop Thirlwall,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24869, line : "\"Greece,\" vol. i. p, 180, that the law of honour among the Greeks"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24870, line : "did not compel them to treasure up in their memory the offensive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24871, line : "language which might be addressed to them by a passionate adversary,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24872, line : "nor to conceive that it left a stain which could only be washed away"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24873, line : "by blood. Even for real and deep injuries they were commonly willing"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24874, line : "to accept a pecuniary compensation.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24876, line : "214 \"The boon of sleep.\"--Milton"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24878, line : "215 \"All else of nature's common gift partake:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24879, line : "Unhappy Dido was alone awake.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24881, line : "--Dryden's Virgil, iv. 767."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24883, line : "216 --_The king of Crete:_ Idomeneus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24885, line : "217 --_Soft wool within, i e._ a kind of woollen stuffing, pressed in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24886, line : "between the straps, to protect the head, and make the helmet fit"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24887, line : "close."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24889, line : "218 \"All the circumstances of this action--the night, Rhesus buried in a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24890, line : "profound sleep, and Diomede with the sword in his hand hanging over"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24891, line : "the head of that prince--furnished Homer with the idea of this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24892, line : "fiction, which represents Rhesus lying fast asleep, and, as it were,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24893, line : "beholding his enemy in a dream, plunging the sword into his bosom."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24894, line : "This image is very natural; for a man in his condition awakes no"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24895, line : "farther than to see confusedly what environs him, and to think it"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24896, line : "not a reality but a dream.\"--Pope."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24898, line : "\"There's one did laugh in his sleep, and one cry'd murder;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24899, line : "They wak'd each other.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24901, line : "--_Macbeth._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24903, line : "219 \"Aurora now had left her saffron bed,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24904, line : "And beams of early light the heavens o'erspread.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24906, line : "Dryden's Virgil, iv. 639"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24908, line : "220 --_Red drops of blood._ \"This phenomenon, if a mere fruit of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24909, line : "poet's imagination, might seem arbitrary or far-fetched. It is one,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24910, line : "however, of ascertained reality, and of no uncommon occurrence in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24911, line : "the climate of Greece.\"--Mure, i p. 493. Cf. Tasso, Gier. Lib. ix."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24912, line : "15:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24914, line : "\"La terra in vece del notturno gelo"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24915, line : "Bagnan rugiade tepide, e sanguigne.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24917, line : "221 \"No thought of flight,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24918, line : "None of retreat, no unbecoming deed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24919, line : "That argued fear.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24921, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 236."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24923, line : "222 --_One of love._ Although a bastard brother received only a small"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24924, line : "portion of the inheritance, he was commonly very well treated. Priam"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24925, line : "appears to be the only one of whom polygamy is directly asserted in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24926, line : "the Iliad. Grote, vol. ii. p. 114, note."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24928, line : "223 \"Circled with foes as when a packe of bloodie jackals cling"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24929, line : "About a goodly palmed hart, hurt with a hunter's bow"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24930, line : "Whose escape his nimble feet insure, whilst his warm blood doth"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24931, line : "flow,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24932, line : "And his light knees have power to move: but (maistred by his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24933, line : "wound)"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24934, line : "Embost within a shady hill, the jackals charge him round,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24935, line : "And teare his flesh--when instantly fortune sends in the powers"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24936, line : "Of some sterne lion, with whose sighte they flie and he devours."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24937, line : "So they around Ulysses prest.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24939, line : "--Chapman."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24941, line : "224 --_Simois, railing,_ &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24943, line : "\"In those bloody fields"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24944, line : "Where Simois rolls the bodies and the shields"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24945, line : "Of heroes.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24947, line : "--Dryden's Virgil, i. 142."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24949, line : "225 \"Where yon disorder'd heap of ruin lies,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24950, line : "Stones rent from stones,--where clouds of dust arise,--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24951, line : "Amid that smother, Neptune holds his place,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24952, line : "Below the wall's foundation drives his mace,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24953, line : "And heaves the building from the solid base.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24955, line : "Dryden's Virgil, ii. 825."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24957, line : "226 --_Why boast we._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24959, line : "\"Wherefore do I assume"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24960, line : "These royalties and not refuse to reign,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24961, line : "Refusing to accept as great a share"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24962, line : "Of hazard as of honour, due alike to him"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24963, line : "Who reigns, and so much to him due"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24964, line : "Of hazard more, as he above the rest"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24965, line : "High honour'd sits.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24967, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" ii. 450."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24969, line : "227 --_Each equal weight._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24971, line : "\"Long time in even scale"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24972, line : "The battle hung.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24974, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 245."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24976, line : "228 \"He on his impious foes right onward drove,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24977, line : "_Gloomy as night._\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24979, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 831"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24981, line : "229 --_Renown'd for justice and for length of days,_ Arrian. de Exp."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24982, line : "Alex. iv. p. 239, also speaks of the independence of these people,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24983, line : "which he regards as the result of their poverty and uprightness."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24984, line : "Some authors have regarded the phrase \"Hippomolgian,\" _i.e._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24985, line : "\"milking their mares,\" as an epithet applicable to numerous tribes,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24986, line : "since the oldest of the Samatian nomads made their mares' milk one"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24987, line : "of their chief articles of diet. The epithet abion or abion, in this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24988, line : "passage, has occasioned much discussion. It may mean, according as"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24989, line : "we read it, either \"long-lived,\" or \"bowless,\" the latter epithet"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24990, line : "indicating that they did not depend upon archery for subsistence."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24992, line : "230 Compare Chapman's quaint, bold verses:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24994, line : "\"And as a round piece of a rocke, which with a winter's flood"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24995, line : "Is from his top torn, when a shoure poured from a bursten cloud,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24996, line : "Hath broke the naturall band it had within the roughftey rock,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24997, line : "Flies jumping all adourne the woods, resounding everie shocke,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24998, line : "And on, uncheckt, it headlong leaps till in a plaine it stay,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 24999, line : "And then (tho' never so impelled), it stirs not any way:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25000, line : "So Hector,--\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25002, line : "231 This book forms a most agreeable interruption to The continuous"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25003, line : "round of battles, which occupy the latter part of the Iliad. It is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25004, line : "as well to observe, that the sameness of these scenes renders many"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25005, line : "notes unnecessary."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25007, line : "232 --_Who to Tydeus owes, i.e._ Diomed."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25009, line : "233 Compare Tasso:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25011, line : "Teneri sdegni, e placide, e tranquille"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25012, line : "Repulse, e cari vezzi, e liete paci,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25013, line : "Sorrisi, parolette, e dolci stille"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25014, line : "Di pianto, e sospir tronchi, e molli baci.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25016, line : "Gier. Lib. xvi. 25"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25018, line : "234 Compare the description of the dwelling of Sleep in Orlando Furioso,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25019, line : "bk. vi."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25021, line : "235 \"Twice seven, the charming daughters of the main--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25022, line : "Around my person wait, and bear my train:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25023, line : "Succeed my wish, and second my design,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25024, line : "The fairest, Deiopeia, shall be thine.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25026, line : "Dryden's Virgil, Ćn. i. 107, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25028, line : "236 --_And Minos._ \"By Homer, Minos is described as the son of Jupiter,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25029, line : "and of the daughter of Phoenix, whom all succeeding authors name"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25030, line : "Europa; and he is thus carried back into the remotest period of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25031, line : "Cretan antiquity known to the poet, apparently as a native hero,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25032, line : "Illustrious enough for a divine parentage, and too ancient to allow"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25033, line : "his descent to be traced to any other source. But in a genealogy"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25034, line : "recorded by later writers, he is likewise the adopted son of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25035, line : "Asterius, as descendant of Dorus, the son of Helen, and is thus"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25036, line : "connected with a colony said to have been led into Creta by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25037, line : "Tentamus, or Tectamus, son of Dorus, who is related either to have"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25038, line : "crossed over from Thessaly, or to have embarked at Malea after"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25039, line : "having led his followers by land into Laconia.\"--Thirlwall, p. 136,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25040, line : "seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25042, line : "237 Milton has emulated this passage, in describing the couch of our"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25043, line : "first parents:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25045, line : "\"Underneath the violet,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25046, line : "Crocus, and hyacinth with rich inlay,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25047, line : "'Broider'd the ground.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25049, line : "--\"Paradise Lost,\" iv. 700."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25051, line : "238 --_He lies protected,_"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25053, line : "\"Forthwith on all sides to his aid was run"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25054, line : "By angels many and strong, who interpos'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25055, line : "Defence, while others bore him on their shields"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25056, line : "Back to his chariot, where it stood retir'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25057, line : "From off the files of war; there they him laid,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25058, line : "Gnashing for anguish, and despite, and shame.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25060, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" vi. 335, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25062, line : "239 --_The brazen dome._ See the note on Bk. viii. Page 142."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25064, line : "240 --_For, by the gods! who flies._ Observe the bold ellipsis of \"he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25065, line : "cries,\" and the transition from the direct to the oblique"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25066, line : "construction. So in Milton:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25068, line : "\"Thus at their shady lodge arriv'd, both stood,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25069, line : "Both turn'd, and under open sky ador'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25070, line : "The God that made both sky, air, earth, and heaven,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25071, line : "Which they beheld, the moon's resplendent globe,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25072, line : "And starry pole.--Thou also mad'st the night,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25073, line : "Maker omnipotent, and thou the day.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25075, line : "Milton, \"Paradise Lost,\" Book iv."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25077, line : "241 --_So some tall rock._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25079, line : "\"But like a rock unmov'd, a rock that braves"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25080, line : "The raging tempest, and the rising waves--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25081, line : "Propp'd on himself he stands: his solid sides"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25082, line : "Wash off the sea-weeds, and the sounding tides.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25084, line : "Dryden's Virgil, vii. 809."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25086, line : "242 Protesilaus was the first Greek who fell, slain by Hector, as he"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25087, line : "leaped from the vessel to the Trojan shore. He was buried on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25088, line : "Chersonese, near the city of Plagusa. Hygin Fab. ciii. Tzetz. on"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25089, line : "Lycophr. 245, 528. There is a most elegant tribute to his memory in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25090, line : "the Preface to the Heroica of Philostratus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25092, line : "243 --_His best beloved._ The following elegant remarks of Thirlwall"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25093, line : "(Greece, vol. i, p. 176 seq.) well illustrate the character of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25094, line : "friendship subsisting between these two heroes--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25096, line : "\"One of the noblest and most amiable sides of the Greek character,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25097, line : "is the readiness with which it lent itself to construct intimate and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25098, line : "durable friendships, and this is a feature no less prominent in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25099, line : "earliest than in later times. It was indeed connected with the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25100, line : "comparatively low estimation in which female society was held; but"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25101, line : "the devotedness and constancy with which these attachments were"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25102, line : "maintained, was not the less admirable and engaging. The heroic"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25103, line : "companions whom we find celebrated partly by Homer and partly in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25104, line : "traditions which, if not of equal antiquity, were grounded on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25105, line : "same feeling, seem to have but one heart and soul, with scarcely a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25106, line : "wish or object apart, and only to live as they are always ready to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25107, line : "die for one another. It is true that the relation between them is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25108, line : "not always one of perfect equality; but this is a circumstance"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25109, line : "which, while it often adds a peculiar charm to the poetical"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25110, line : "description, detracts little from the dignity of the idea which it"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25111, line : "presents. Such were the friendships of Hercules and Iolaus, of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25112, line : "Theseus and Pirithous, of Orestes and Pylades; and though These may"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25113, line : "owe the greater part of their fame to the later epic or even"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25114, line : "dramatic poetry, the moral groundwork undoubtedly subsisted in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25115, line : "period to which the traditions are referred. The argument of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25116, line : "Iliad mainly turns on the affection of Achilles for Patroclus, whose"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25117, line : "love for the greater hero is only tempered by reverence for his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25118, line : "higher birth and his unequalled prowess. But the mutual regard which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25119, line : "united Idomeneus and Meriones, Diomedes and Sthenelus, though, as"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25120, line : "the persons themselves are less important, it is kept more in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25121, line : "back-ground, is manifestly viewed by the poet in the same light. The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25122, line : "idea of a Greek hero seems not to have been thought complete,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25123, line : "without such a brother in arms by his side.\"--Thirlwall, Greece, vol."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25124, line : "i. p. 176, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25126, line : "244 \"As hungry wolves with raging appetite,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25127, line : "Scour through the fields, ne'er fear the stormy night--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25128, line : "Their whelps at home expect the promised food,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25129, line : "And long to temper their dry chaps in blood--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25130, line : "So rush'd we forth at once.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25132, line : "--Dryden's Virgil, ii. 479."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25134, line : "245 --_The destinies ordain._--\"In the mythology, also, of the Iliad,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25135, line : "purely Pagan as it is, we discover one important truth unconsciously"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25136, line : "involved, which was almost entirely lost from view amidst the nearly"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25137, line : "equal scepticism and credulity of subsequent ages. Zeus or Jupiter"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25138, line : "is popularly to be taken as omnipotent. No distinct empire is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25139, line : "assigned to fate or fortune; the will of the father of gods and men"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25140, line : "is absolute and uncontrollable. This seems to be the true character"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25141, line : "of the Homeric deity, and it is very necessary that the student of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25142, line : "Greek literature should bear it constantly in mind. A strong"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25143, line : "instance in the Iliad itself to illustrate this position, is the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25144, line : "passage where Jupiter laments to Juno the approaching death of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25145, line : "Sarpedon. 'Alas me!' says he 'since it is fated (moira) that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25146, line : "Sarpedon, dearest to me of men, should be slain by Patroclus, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25147, line : "son of Menoetius! Indeed, my heart is divided within me while I"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25148, line : "ruminate it in my mind, whether having snatched him up from out of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25149, line : "the lamentable battle, I should not at once place him alive in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25150, line : "fertile land of his own Lycia, or whether I should now destroy him"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25151, line : "by the hands of the son of Menoetius!' To which Juno answers--'Dost"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25152, line : "thou mean to rescue from death a mortal man, long since destined by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25153, line : "fate (palai pepromenon)? You may do it--but we, the rest of the gods,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25154, line : "do not sanction it.' Here it is clear from both speakers, that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25155, line : "although Sarpedon is said to be fated to die, Jupiter might still,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25156, line : "if he pleased, save him, and place him entirely out of the reach of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25157, line : "any such event, and further, in the alternative, that Jupiter"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25158, line : "himself would destroy him by the hands of another.\"--Coleridge, p."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25159, line : "156. seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25161, line : "246 --_Thrice at the battlements._ \"The art military of the Homeric age"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25162, line : "is upon a level with the state of navigation just described,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25163, line : "personal prowess decided every thing; the night attack and the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25164, line : "ambuscade, although much esteemed, were never upon a large scale."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25165, line : "The chiefs fight in advance, and enact almost as much as the knights"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25166, line : "of romance. The siege of Troy was as little like a modern siege as a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25167, line : "captain in the guards is like Achilles. There is no mention of a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25168, line : "ditch or any other line or work round the town, and the wall itself"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25169, line : "was accessible without a ladder. It was probably a vast mound of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25170, line : "earth with a declivity outwards. Patroclus thrice mounts it in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25171, line : "armour. The Trojans are in no respects blockaded, and receive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25172, line : "assistance from their allies to the very end.\"--Coleridge, p. 212."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25174, line : "247 --_Ciconians._--A people of Thrace, near the Hebrus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25176, line : "248 --_They wept._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25178, line : "\"Fast by the manger stands the inactive steed,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25179, line : "And, sunk in sorrow, hangs his languid head;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25180, line : "He stands, and careless of his golden grain,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25181, line : "Weeps his associates and his master slain.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25183, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, v. 18-24."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25185, line : "\"Nothing is heard upon the mountains now,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25186, line : "But pensive herds that for their master low,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25187, line : "Straggling and comfortless about they rove,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25188, line : "Unmindful of their pasture and their love.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25190, line : "Moschus, id. 3, parodied, _ibid._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25192, line : "\"To close the pomp, Ćthon, the steed of state,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25193, line : "Is led, the funeral of his lord to wait."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25194, line : "Stripp'd of his trappings, with a sullen pace"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25195, line : "He walks, and the big tears run rolling down his face.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25197, line : "Dryden's Virgil, bk. ii"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25199, line : "249 --_Some brawny bull._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25201, line : "\"Like to a bull, that with impetuous spring"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25202, line : "Darts, at the moment when the fatal blow"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25203, line : "Hath struck him, but unable to proceed"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25204, line : "Plunges on either side.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25206, line : "--Carey's Dante: Hell, c. xii."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25208, line : "250 This is connected with the earlier part of last book, the regular"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25209, line : "narrative being interrupted by the message of Antilochus and the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25210, line : "lamentations of Achilles."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25212, line : "251 --_Far in the deep._ So Oceanus hears the lamentations of Prometheus,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25213, line : "in the play of Ćschylus, and comes from the depths of the sea to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25214, line : "comfort him."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25216, line : "252 Opuntia, a city of Locris."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25218, line : "253 Quintus Calaber, lib. v., has attempted to rival Homer in his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25219, line : "description of the shield of the same hero. A few extracts from Mr."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25220, line : "Dyce's version (Select Translations, p. 104, seq.) may here be"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25221, line : "introduced."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25223, line : "\"In the wide circle of the shield were seen"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25224, line : "Refulgent images of various forms,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25225, line : "The work of Vulcan; who had there described"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25226, line : "The heaven, the ether, and the earth and sea,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25227, line : "The winds, the clouds, the moon, the sun, apart"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25228, line : "In different stations; and you there might view"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25229, line : "The stars that gem the still-revolving heaven,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25230, line : "And, under them, the vast expanse of air,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25231, line : "In which, with outstretch'd wings, the long-beak'd bird"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25232, line : "Winnow'd the gale, as if instinct with life."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25233, line : "Around the shield the waves of ocean flow'd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25234, line : "The realms of Tethys, which unnumber'd streams,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25235, line : "In azure mazes rolling o'er the earth,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25236, line : "Seem'd to augment.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25238, line : "254 --_On seats of stone._ \"Several of the old northern Sagas represent"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25239, line : "the old men assembled for the purpose of judging as sitting on great"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25240, line : "stones, in a circle called the Urtheilsring or gerichtsring\"-- Grote,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25241, line : "ii. p. 100, note. On the independence of the judicial office in The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25242, line : "heroic times, see Thirlwall's Greece, vol. i. p. 166."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25244, line : "255 --_Another part,_ &c."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25246, line : "\"And here"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25247, line : "Were horrid wars depicted; grimly pale"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25248, line : "Were heroes lying with their slaughter'd steeds"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25249, line : "Upon the ground incarnadin'd with blood."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25250, line : "Stern stalked Bellona, smear'd with reeking gore,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25251, line : "Through charging ranks; beside her Rout was seen,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25252, line : "And Terror, Discord to the fatal strife"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25253, line : "Inciting men, and Furies breathing flames:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25254, line : "Nor absent were the Fates, and the tall shape"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25255, line : "Of ghastly Death, round whom did Battles throng,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25256, line : "Their limbs distilling plenteous blood and sweat;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25257, line : "And Gorgons, whose long locks were twisting snakes."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25258, line : "That shot their forky tongues incessant forth."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25259, line : "Such were the horrors of dire war.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25261, line : "--Dyce's Calaber."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25263, line : "256 --_A field deep furrowed._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25265, line : "\"Here was a corn field; reapers in a row,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25266, line : "Each with a sharp-tooth'd sickle in his hand,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25267, line : "Work'd busily, and, as the harvest fell,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25268, line : "Others were ready still to bind the sheaves:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25269, line : "Yoked to a wain that bore the corn away"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25270, line : "The steers were moving; sturdy bullocks here"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25271, line : "The plough were drawing, and the furrow'd glebe"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25272, line : "Was black behind them, while with goading wand"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25273, line : "The active youths impell'd them. Here a feast"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25274, line : "Was graved: to the shrill pipe and ringing lyre"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25275, line : "A band of blooming virgins led the dance."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25276, line : "As if endued with life.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25278, line : "--Dyce's Calaber."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25280, line : "257 Coleridge (Greek Classic Poets, p. 182, seq.) has diligently"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25281, line : "compared this with the description of the shield of Hercules by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25282, line : "Hesiod. He remarks that, \"with two or three exceptions, the imagery"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25283, line : "differs in little more than the names and arrangements; and the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25284, line : "difference of arrangement in the Shield of Hercules is altogether"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25285, line : "for the worse. The natural consecution of the Homeric images needs"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25286, line : "no exposition: it constitutes in itself one of the beauties of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25287, line : "work. The Hesiodic images are huddled together without connection or"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25288, line : "congruity: Mars and Pallas are awkwardly introduced among the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25289, line : "Centaurs and Lapithae;-- but the gap is wide indeed between them and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25290, line : "Apollo with the Muses, waking the echoes of Olympus to celestial"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25291, line : "harmonies; whence however, we are hurried back to Perseus, the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25292, line : "Gorgons, and other images of war, over an arm of the sea, in which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25293, line : "the sporting dolphins, the fugitive fishes, and the fisherman on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25294, line : "shore with his casting net, are minutely represented. As to the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25295, line : "Hesiodic images themselves, the leading remark is, that they catch"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25296, line : "at beauty by ornament, and at sublimity by exaggeration; and upon"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25297, line : "the untenable supposition of the genuineness of this poem, there is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25298, line : "this curious peculiarity, that, in the description of scenes of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25299, line : "rustic peace, the superiority of Homer is decisive--while in those of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25300, line : "war and tumult it may be thought, perhaps, that the Hesiodic poet"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25301, line : "has more than once the advantage.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25303, line : "258 \"This legend is one of the most pregnant and characteristic in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25304, line : "Grecian Mythology; it explains, according to the religious ideas"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25305, line : "familiar to the old epic poets, both the distinguishing attributes"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25306, line : "and the endless toil and endurances of Heracles, the most renowned"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25307, line : "subjugator of all the semi-divine personages worshipped by the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25308, line : "Hellenes,--a being of irresistible force, and especially beloved by"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25309, line : "Zeus, yet condemned constantly to labour for others and to obey the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25310, line : "commands of a worthless and cowardly persecutor. His recompense is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25311, line : "reserved to the close of his career, when his afflicting trials are"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25312, line : "brought to a close: he is then admitted to the godhead, and receives"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25313, line : "in marriage Hebe.\"--Grote, vol. i. p. 128."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25315, line : "259 --_Ambrosia._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25317, line : "\"The blue-eyed maid,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25318, line : "In ev'ry breast new vigour to infuse."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25319, line : "Brings nectar temper'd with ambrosial dews.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25321, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, vi. 249."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25323, line : "260 \"Hell is naked before him, and destruction hath no covering. He"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25324, line : "stretcheth out the north over the empty place, and hangeth the earth"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25325, line : "upon nothing. He bindeth up the waters in his thick clouds; and the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25326, line : "cloud is not rent under them.\" Job xxvi. 6-8."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25328, line : "261 \"Swift from his throne the infernal monarch ran,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25329, line : "All pale and trembling, lest the race of man,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25330, line : "Slain by Jove's wrath, and led by Hermes' rod,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25331, line : "Should fill (a countless throng!) his dark abode.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25333, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, vi. 769, sqq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25335, line : "262 These words seem to imply the old belief, that the Fates might be"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25336, line : "delayed, but never wholly set aside."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25338, line : "263 It was anciently believed that it was dangerous, if not fatal, to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25339, line : "behold a deity. See Exod. xxxiii. 20; Judg. xiii. 22."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25341, line : "264 \"Ere Ilium and the Trojan tow'rs arose,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25342, line : "In humble vales they built their soft abodes.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25344, line : "Dryden's Virgil, iii. 150."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25346, line : "265 --_Along the level seas._ Compare Virgil's description of Camilla,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25347, line : "who"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25349, line : "\"Outstripp'd the winds in speed upon the plain,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25350, line : "Flew o'er the field, nor hurt the bearded grain:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25351, line : "She swept the seas, and, as she skimm'd along,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25352, line : "Her flying feet unbathed on billows hung.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25354, line : "Dryden, vii. 1100."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25356, line : "266 --_The future father._ \"Ćneas and Antenor stand distinguished from"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25357, line : "the other Trojans by a dissatisfaction with Priam, and a sympathy"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25358, line : "with the Greeks, which is by Sophocles and others construed as"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25359, line : "treacherous collusion,--a suspicion indirectly glanced at, though"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25360, line : "emphatically repelled, in the Ćneas of Virgil.\"--Grote, i. p. 427."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25362, line : "267 Neptune thus recounts his services to Ćneas:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25364, line : "\"When your Ćneas fought, but fought with odds"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25365, line : "Of force unequal, and unequal gods:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25366, line : "I spread a cloud before the victor's sight,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25367, line : "Sustain'd the vanquish'd, and secured his flight--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25368, line : "Even then secured him, when I sought with joy"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25369, line : "The vow'd destruction of ungrateful Troy.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25371, line : "Dryden's Virgil, v. 1058."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25373, line : "268 --_On Polydore._ Euripides, Virgil, and others, relate that Polydore"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25374, line : "was sent into Thrace, to the house of Polymestor, for protection,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25375, line : "being the youngest of Priam's sons, and that he was treacherously"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25376, line : "murdered by his host for the sake of the treasure sent with him."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25378, line : "269 \"Perhaps the boldest excursion of Homer into this region of poetical"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25379, line : "fancy is the collision into which, in the twenty-first of the Iliad,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25380, line : "he has brought the river god Scamander, first with Achilles, and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25381, line : "afterwards with Vulcan, when summoned by Juno to the hero's aid. The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25382, line : "overwhelming fury of the stream finds the natural interpretation in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25383, line : "the character of the mountain torrents of Greece and Asia Minor."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25384, line : "Their wide, shingly beds are in summer comparatively dry, so as to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25385, line : "be easily forded by the foot passenger. But a thunder-shower in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25386, line : "mountains, unobserved perhaps by the traveller on the plain, may"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25387, line : "suddenly immerse him in the flood of a mighty river. The rescue of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25388, line : "Achilles by the fiery arms of Vulcan scarcely admits of the same"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25389, line : "ready explanation from physical causes. Yet the subsiding of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25390, line : "flood at the critical moment when the hero's destruction appeared"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25391, line : "imminent, might, by a slight extension of the figurative parallel,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25392, line : "be ascribed to a god symbolic of the influences opposed to all"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25393, line : "atmospheric moisture.\"--Mure, vol. i. p. 480, sq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25395, line : "270 Wood has observed, that \"the circumstance of a falling tree, which"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25396, line : "is described as reaching from one of its banks to the other, affords"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25397, line : "a very just idea of the breadth of the Scamander.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25399, line : "271 --_Ignominious._ Drowning, as compared with a death in the field of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25400, line : "battle, was considered utterly disgraceful."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25402, line : "272 --_Beneath a caldron._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25404, line : "\"So, when with crackling flames a caldron fries,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25405, line : "The bubbling waters from the bottom rise."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25406, line : "Above the brims they force their fiery way;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25407, line : "Black vapours climb aloft, and cloud the day.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25409, line : "Dryden's Virgil, vii. 644."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25411, line : "273 \"This tale of the temporary servitude of particular gods, by order"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25412, line : "of Jove, as a punishment for misbehaviour, recurs not unfrequently"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25413, line : "among the incidents of the Mythical world.\"--Grote, vol. i. p. 156."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25415, line : "274 --_Not half so dreadful._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25417, line : "\"On the other side,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25418, line : "Incensed with indignation, Satan stood"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25419, line : "Unterrified, and like a comet burn'd,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25420, line : "That fires the length of Ophiuchus huge"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25421, line : "In the arctic sky, and from his horrid hair"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25422, line : "Shakes pestilence and war.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25424, line : "--Paradise Lost,\" xi. 708."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25426, line : "275 \"And thus his own undaunted mind explores.\"--\"Paradise Lost,\" vi."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25427, line : "113."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25429, line : "276 The example of Nausicaa, in the Odyssey, proves that the duties of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25430, line : "the laundry were not thought derogatory, even from the dignity of a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25431, line : "princess, in the heroic times."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25433, line : "277 --_Hesper shines with keener light._"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25435, line : "\"Fairest of stars, last in the train of night,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25436, line : "If better thou belong not to the dawn.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25438, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" v. 166."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25440, line : "278 Such was his fate. After chasing the Trojans into the town, he was"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25441, line : "slain by an arrow from the quiver of Paris, directed under the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25442, line : "unerring auspices of Apollo. The greatest efforts were made by the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25443, line : "Trojans to possess themselves of the body, which was however rescued"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25444, line : "and borne off to the Grecian camp by the valour of Ajax and Ulysses."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25445, line : "Thetis stole away the body, just as the Greeks were about to burn it"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25446, line : "with funeral honours, and conveyed it away to a renewed life of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25447, line : "immortality in the isle of Leuke in the Euxine."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25449, line : "279 --_Astyanax,_ i.e. the _city-king_ or guardian. It is amusing that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25450, line : "Plato, who often finds fault with Homer without reason, should have"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25451, line : "copied this twaddling etymology into his Cratylus."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25453, line : "280 This book has been closely imitated by Virgil in his fifth book, but"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25454, line : "it is almost useless to attempt a selection of passages for"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25455, line : "comparison."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25457, line : "281 --_Thrice in order led._ This was a frequent rite at funerals. The"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25458, line : "Romans had the same custom, which they called _decursio._ Plutarch"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25459, line : "states that Alexander, in after times, renewed these same honours to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25460, line : "the memory of Achilles himself."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25462, line : "282 --_And swore._ Literally, and called Orcus, the god of oaths, to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25463, line : "witness. See Buttmann, Lexilog, p. 436."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25465, line : "283 \"O, long expected by thy friends! from whence"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25466, line : "Art thou so late return'd for our defence?"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25467, line : "Do we behold thee, wearied as we are"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25468, line : "With length of labours, and with, toils of war?"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25469, line : "After so many funerals of thy own,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25470, line : "Art thou restored to thy declining town?"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25471, line : "But say, what wounds are these? what new disgrace"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25472, line : "Deforms the manly features of thy face?\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25474, line : "Dryden, xi. 369."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25476, line : "284 --_Like a thin smoke._ Virgil, Georg. iv. 72."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25478, line : "\"In vain I reach my feeble hands to join"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25479, line : "In sweet embraces--ah! no longer thine!"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25480, line : "She said, and from his eyes the fleeting fair"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25481, line : "Retired, like subtle smoke dissolved in air.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25483, line : "Dryden."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25485, line : "285 So Milton:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25487, line : "\"So eagerly the fiend"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25488, line : "O'er bog, o'er steep, through strait, rough, dense, or rare,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25489, line : "With head, hands, wings, or feet pursues his way,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25490, line : "And swims, or sinks, or wades, or creeps, or flies.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25492, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" ii. 948."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25494, line : "286 \"An ancient forest, for the work design'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25495, line : "(The shady covert of the savage kind)."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25496, line : "The Trojans found: the sounding axe is placed:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25497, line : "Firs, pines, and pitch-trees, and the tow'ring pride"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25498, line : "Of forest ashes, feel the fatal stroke,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25499, line : "And piercing wedges cleave the stubborn oak."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25500, line : "High trunks of trees, fell'd from the steepy crown"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25501, line : "Of the bare mountains, roll with ruin down.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25503, line : "Dryden's Virgil, vi. 261."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25505, line : "287 --_He vowed._ This was a very ancient custom."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25507, line : "288 The height of the tomb or pile was a great proof of the dignity of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25508, line : "the deceased, and the honour in which he was held."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25510, line : "289 On the prevalence of this cruel custom amongst the northern nations,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25511, line : "see Mallet, p. 213."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25513, line : "290 --_And calls the spirit._ Such was the custom anciently, even at the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25514, line : "Roman funerals."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25516, line : "\"Hail, O ye holy manes! hail again,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25517, line : "Paternal ashes, now revived in vain.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25519, line : "Dryden's Virgil, v. 106."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25521, line : "291 Virgil, by making the boaster vanquished, has drawn a better moral"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25522, line : "from this episode than Homer. The following lines deserve"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25523, line : "comparison:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25525, line : "\"The haughty Dares in the lists appears:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25526, line : "Walking he strides, his head erected bears:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25527, line : "His nervous arms the weighty gauntlet wield,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25528, line : "And loud applauses echo through the field."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25529, line : "*          *          *          *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25530, line : "Such Dares was, and such he strode along,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25531, line : "And drew the wonder of the gazing throng"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25532, line : "His brawny breast and ample chest he shows;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25533, line : "His lifted arms around his head he throws,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25534, line : "And deals in whistling air his empty blows."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25535, line : "His match is sought, but, through the trembling band,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25536, line : "No one dares answer to the proud demand."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25537, line : "Presuming of his force, with sparkling eyes,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25538, line : "Already he devours the promised prize."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25539, line : "*          *          *          *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25540, line : "If none my matchless valour dares oppose,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25541, line : "How long shall Dares wait his dastard foes?\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25543, line : "Dryden's Virgil, v. 486, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25545, line : "292 \"The gauntlet-fight thus ended, from the shore"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25546, line : "His faithful friends unhappy Dares bore:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25547, line : "His mouth and nostrils pour'd a purple flood,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25548, line : "And pounded teeth came rushing with his blood.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25550, line : "Dryden's Virgil, v. 623."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25552, line : "293 \"Troilus is only once named in the Iliad; he was mentioned also in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25553, line : "the Cypriad but his youth, beauty, and untimely end made him an"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25554, line : "object of great interest with the subsequent poets.\"--Grote, i, p."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25555, line : "399."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25557, line : "294 Milton has rivalled this passage describing the descent of Gabriel,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25558, line : "\"Paradise Lost,\" bk. v. 266, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25560, line : "\"Down thither prone in flight"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25561, line : "He speeds, and through the vast ethereal sky"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25562, line : "Sails between worlds and worlds, with steady wing,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25563, line : "Now on the polar winds, then with quick fan"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25564, line : "Winnows the buxom air. * * * *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25565, line : "*           *               *             *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25566, line : "At once on th' eastern cliff of Paradise"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25567, line : "He lights, and to his proper shape returns"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25568, line : "A seraph wing'd. * * * *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25569, line : "Like Maia's son he stood,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25570, line : "And shook his plumes, that heavenly fragrance fill'd"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25571, line : "The circuit wide.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25573, line : "Virgil, Ćn. iv. 350:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25575, line : "\"Hermes obeys; with golden pinions binds"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25576, line : "His flying feet, and mounts the western winds:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25577, line : "And whether o'er the seas or earth he flies,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25578, line : "With rapid force they bear him down the skies"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25579, line : "But first he grasps within his awful hand"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25580, line : "The mark of sovereign power, his magic wand;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25581, line : "With this he draws the ghost from hollow graves;"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25582, line : "With this he drives them from the Stygian waves:"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25583, line : "*           *               *             *"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25584, line : "Thus arm'd, the god begins his airy race,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25585, line : "And drives the racking clouds along the liquid space.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25587, line : "Dryden."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25589, line : "295 In reference to the whole scene that follows, the remarks of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25590, line : "Coleridge are well worth reading:--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25592, line : "\"By a close study of life, and by a true and natural mode of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25593, line : "expressing everything, Homer was enabled to venture upon the most"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25594, line : "peculiar and difficult situations, and to extricate himself from"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25595, line : "them with the completest success. The whole scene between Achilles"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25596, line : "and Priam, when the latter comes to the Greek camp for the purpose"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25597, line : "of redeeming the body of Hector, is at once the most profoundly"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25598, line : "skilful, and yet the simplest and most affecting passage in the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25599, line : "Iliad. Quinctilian has taken notice of the following speech of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25600, line : "Priam, the rhetorical artifice of which is so transcendent, that if"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25601, line : "genius did not often, especially in oratory, unconsciously fulfil"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25602, line : "the most subtle precepts of criticism, we might be induced, on this"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25603, line : "account alone, to consider the last book of the Iliad as what is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25604, line : "called spurious, in other words, of later date than the rest of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25605, line : "poem. Observe the exquisite taste of Priam in occupying the mind of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25606, line : "Achilles, from the outset, with the image of his father; in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25607, line : "gradually introducing the parallel of his own situation; and,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25608, line : "lastly, mentioning Hector's name when he perceives that the hero is"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25609, line : "softened, and then only in such a manner as to flatter the pride of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25610, line : "the conqueror. The ego d'eleeinoteros per, and the apusato aecha"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25611, line : "geronta, are not exactly like the tone of the earlier parts of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25612, line : "Iliad. They are almost too fine and pathetic. The whole passage"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25613, line : "defies translation, for there is that about the Greek which has no"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25614, line : "name, but which is of so fine and ethereal a subtlety that it can"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25615, line : "only be felt in the original, and is lost in an attempt to transfuse"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25616, line : "it into another language.\"--Coleridge, p. 195."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25618, line : "296 \"Achilles' ferocious treatment of the corpse of Hector cannot but"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25619, line : "offend as referred to the modern standard of humanity. The heroic"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25620, line : "age, however, must be judged by its own moral laws. Retributive"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25621, line : "vengeance on the dead, as well as the living, was a duty inculcated"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25622, line : "by the religion of those barbarous times which not only taught that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25623, line : "evil inflicted on the author of evil was a solace to the injured"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25624, line : "man; but made the welfare of the soul after death dependent on the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25625, line : "fate of the body from which it had separated. Hence a denial of the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25626, line : "rites essential to the soul's admission into the more favoured"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25627, line : "regions of the lower world was a cruel punishment to the wanderer on"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25628, line : "the dreary shores of the infernal river. The complaint of the ghost"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25629, line : "of Patroclus to Achilles, of but a brief postponement of his own"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25630, line : "obsequies, shows how efficacious their refusal to the remains of his"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25631, line : "destroyer must have been in satiating the thirst of revenge, which,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25632, line : "even after death, was supposed to torment the dwellers in Hades."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25633, line : "Hence before yielding up the body of Hector to Priam, Achilles asks"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25634, line : "pardon of Patroclus for even this partial cession of his just rights"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25635, line : "of retribution.\"--Mure, vol. i. 289."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25637, line : "297 Such was the fate of Astyanax, when Troy was taken."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25639, line : "\"Here, from the tow'r by stern Ulysses thrown,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25640, line : "Andromache bewail'd her infant son.\""});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25642, line : "Merrick's Tryphiodorus, v. 675."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25644, line : "298 The following observations of Coleridge furnish a most gallant and"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25645, line : "interesting view of Helen's character--"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25647, line : "\"Few things are more interesting than to observe how the same hand"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25648, line : "that has given us the fury and inconsistency of Achilles, gives us"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25649, line : "also the consummate elegance and tenderness of Helen. She is through"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25650, line : "the Iliad a genuine lady, graceful in motion and speech, noble in"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25651, line : "her associations, full of remorse for a fault for which higher"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25652, line : "powers seem responsible, yet grateful and affectionate towards those"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25653, line : "with whom that fault had committed her. I have always thought the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25654, line : "following speech in which Helen laments Hector, and hints at her own"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25655, line : "invidious and unprotected situation in Troy, as almost the sweetest"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25656, line : "passage in the poem. It is another striking instance of that"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25657, line : "refinement of feeling and softness of tone which so generally"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25658, line : "distinguish the last book of the Iliad from the rest.\"--Classic"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25659, line : "Poets, p. 198, seq."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25661, line : "299 \"And here we part with Achilles at the moment best calculated to"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25662, line : "exalt and purify our impression of his character. We had accompanied"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25663, line : "him through the effervescence, undulations, and final subsidence of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25664, line : "his stormy passions. We now leave him in repose and under the full"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25665, line : "influence of the more amiable affections, while our admiration of"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25666, line : "his great qualities is chastened by the reflection that, within a"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25667, line : "few short days the mighty being in whom they were united was himself"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25668, line : "to be suddenly cut off in the full vigour of their exercise."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25670, line : "The frequent and touching allusions, interspersed throughout the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25671, line : "Iliad, to the speedy termination of its hero's course, and the moral"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25672, line : "on the vanity of human life which they indicate, are among the"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25673, line : "finest evidences of the spirit of ethic unity by which the whole"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25674, line : "framework of the poem is united.\"--Mure, vol. i. p 201."});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25676, line : "300 Cowper says,--\"I cannot take my leave of this noble poem without"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25677, line : "expressing how much I am struck with the plain conclusion of it. It"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25678, line : "is like the exit of a great man out of company, whom he has"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25679, line : "entertained magnificently; neither pompous nor familiar; not"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25680, line : "contemptuous, yet without much ceremony.\" Coleridge, p. 227,"});
db.iliad.insert({ pg : 25681, line : "considers the termination of \"Paradise Lost\" somewhat similar."});
